# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2020-thuringian-government-crisis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The **2019 Thuringian state election** was held on 27 October 2019 to elect the members of the 7th Landtag of Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The outgoing government was a coalition consisting of The Left, the Social Democratic Party (SPD), and The Greens, led by Minister-President Bodo Ramelow.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The Left became the largest party for the first time in any German state with a small improvement to 31% of votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) more than doubled its vote share to 23%, overtaking the opposition Christian Democratic Union (CDU) to place second.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The CDU suffered major losses, falling from 33% to 22%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The SPD also declined, while the Greens and Free Democratic Party (FDP) narrowly passed the 5% electoral threshold – the Greens retaining their seats, while the FDP re-entered the Landtag after falling out in 2014.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The election resulted in a hung parliament, as the previous governing coalition fell four seats short of an overall majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] No majority can be formed without the involvement of at least two of The Left, AfD, and CDU, all of whom explicitly ruled out cooperation with one another.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] As a result, no viable majority was considered to exist.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] On 5 February 2020, the Landtag voted to elect the Minister-President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Incumbent Ramelow was expected to be re-elected to lead a minority government on the third ballot, which requires only a plurality to pass.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The CDU declined to run a candidate, and neither the AfD's candidate nor FDP leader Thomas Kemmerich were expected to garner enough support to win.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] However, on the third ballot, Kemmerich was unexpectedly elected, winning 45 votes to incumbent Ramelow's 44.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The votes for Kemmerich came from the FDP, CDU, and AfD, whose candidate, a fairly obscure local mayor, got no votes in the third round, all AfD MdLs tactically supporting Kemmerich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This was the first time the AfD had been involved in the election of a head of government in Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This was highly controversial, sparking protest throughout both Thuringia and Germany and condemnation from politicians nationwide, including federal Chancellor Angela Merkel, who described it as "unforgivable".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Under intense pressure, Kemmerich announced his resignation just two days later but remained in office in a caretaker capacity until the Landtag could elect another Minister-President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] On 4 March, a second vote was held, and Bodo Ramelow was re-elected as Minister-President with the abstentions of the CDU and FDP.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] On 28 August 2018, the Thuringian Land government announced that the election was to take place on 27 October 2019.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The Left became the strongest party in a state election for the first time since German reunification.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The FDP won seats in an eastern state parliament for the first time since the 2009 Brandenburg state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Whether the FDP would pass the 5% electoral threshold was unclear for much of election night, but the preliminary results showed them entering the Landtag by a margin of just six votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This increased to 73 votes in the final results announced on 7 November.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The AfD doubled its performance from 10.6% and 11 seats to 23.4% and 22 seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The CDU, which had been the largest party in Thuringia since the state's first election in 1990 and had governed uninterrupted until 2014, suffered its worst ever result.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] It lost more than 11 percentage points and fell to third place, winning just 22.5% of the vote; clearly missing its goal of returning to the head of the Thuringian government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] She stated she was "devastated" by the huge gains made by the AfD, referring to the party as "fascistic".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The AfD was described as such at various times in the aftermath of the election by both participants and observers.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This was particularly true of their state leader Björn Höcke due to his comments and publications, as well as a recent court ruling which stated that the description of Höcke as a fascist "rests on verifiable fact".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The red-red-green coalition of The Left, the SPD, and The Greens which previously governed the state lost their majority in the legislature, and are a total of four seats short.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The CDU ruled out cooperation with the Left, and all parties ruled out any cooperation with AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] An open letter published on 5 November, signed by 17 state CDU members, caused controversy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The letter urged the CDU to hold discussions with "all democratically elected parties" in the Landtag before ruling out any coalition partnerships, and was criticized by members of the national CDU and other parties, who interpreted it as a veiled call to work with AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Earlier in the week, deputy state party leader Michael Heym also publicly suggested exploring the possibility of a CDU–AfD–FDP coalition.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The result provided for two possible majority governments not including AfD: a Left–CDU coalition (also potentially including the SPD and/or Greens), or a Left–SPD–Green–FDP coalition.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The former would be ideologically unwieldy but command a stable majority, while the latter had only been tried on local level, and would only hold a slim majority of two seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Both were considered infeasible due to ideological differences and pledges made by both the CDU and FDP not to work with The Left.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Minister-President Ramelow invited CDU leader Mohring to formal exploratory talks during the week of 4 November, but withdrew the invitation on 9 November, claiming Mohring had violated discretion by publicly displaying text messages between them.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] At the same time, CDU state secretary general Raymond Walk reiterated his party's rejection of any partnership with the Left.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] After the breakdown of coalition talks, Ramelow announced his intention to continue leading a red-red-green minority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] At the opening of parliament on 5 February 2020, Ramelow stood for election as Minister-President, while the AfD nominated independent local mayor Christoph Kindervater.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The election process involves two ballots in which a candidate requires an absolute majority (46 affirmative votes) to be elected, after which a third and final ballot requires only a plurality.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] FDP leader Thomas Kemmerich announced he would also stand on this third ballot if one were held.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Ramelow received 43 votes on the first ballot and 44 on the second, short of a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Kindervater received 25 votes on the first ballot and 22 on the second.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The FDP and CDU abstained from both the first and second ballots.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Kemmerich entered the contest on the third ballot.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] He received the support of the CDU, FDP, and AfD, being elected with 45 votes, while Ramelow received 44.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This was highly unexpected, as neither the CDU or AfD had publicly expressed any intention to support Kemmerich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The CDU was expected to abstain on the third ballot as it did on the first two.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The AfD did not withdraw their candidate Kindervater on the third ballot; he stood, but received no votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This marked the first time a state head of government had been elected with the support of the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The leftist parties as well as some within the federal FDP sharply criticized the CDU for breaking the *cordon sanitaire* surrounding the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Previously, there had been a general agreement among all other parties that the AfD should be denied any influence in government, and should not be negotiated nor worked with on any level.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The apparent cooperation between the three parties in Thuringia was viewed as having broken this agreement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The Left and Greens immediately ruled out working with Kemmerich, and called for new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Outgoing Minister-President Ramelow drew parallels between AfD's role in Kemmerich's election and the rise of the Nazi Party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Protests were held in several German cities after the election, including in the Thuringian capital of Erfurt, where 1,000 protestors demonstrated outside the Landtag as Kemmerich delivered his acceptance speech.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Federal SPD leaders Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken stated they would withdraw their party from the federal CDU–SPD government if Kemmerich did not resign immediately.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Federal CDU leader Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer criticized the state CDU for "[acting] against the wishes" of the federal party, and raised the possibility of new elections as the "cleanest" way to break the deadlock.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] In a later statement on Twitter, she asked state CDU legislators to abstain from participating in a Kemmerich cabinet and directly called for new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Federal Chancellor Angela Merkel, on a state visit to South Africa when the vote took place, condemned it in a statement: "It was a bad day for democracy, a day that broke with the long and proud tradition of the CDU's values.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This is in no way in line with what the CDU thinks, how we have acted throughout our party's existence." Christian Hirte, federal commissioner for the new states of Germany, was dismissed from cabinet after tweeting his congratulations to Kemmerich after the election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] A letter sent to Kemmerich by AfD leader Björn Höcke shortly after the 2019 election led to speculation that AfD's support for Kemmerich was planned and coordinated.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] In the letter, Höcke offered AfD support for either a non-partisan technocratic government or an FDP minority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Despite this, Kemmerich and his party denied having any knowledge of AfD's intentions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] On 8 February, Kemmerich announced his resignation and stated his support for new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Despite his resignation, Kemmerich remained in office in a caretaker capacity until the Landtag could hold a new election for Minister-President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The Left and CDU held talks on 17 February, seeking to resolve the crisis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Bodo Ramelow suggested that former CDU Minister-President Christine Lieberknecht lead a three-member transitional cabinet which would serve until a new election was held, which he suggested should take place 70 days later.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The CDU rejected this prospect, stating that a full cabinet should take office and that a state budget should be passed before new elections are held.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Following further discussions, The Left, CDU, SPD, and Greens announced on 21 February 2020 that they had reached an agreement to hold a new election for Minister-President on 4 March 2020, and a new state election on 25 April 2021.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] The four parties stated they would support Bodo Ramelow for Minister-President, and that he should lead an interim government for the next 13 months until the election is held.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] This government would comprise the same red-red-green arrangement which governed Thuringia from 2014 to February 2020 and had to pass a budget together with the CDU, before the new election would be called by dissolving the parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] Between them, the four parties held 63 of the 90 seats in the Landtag (70%), more than the two-thirds required to dissolve the Landtag and trigger an early election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] On 2 March, Björn Höcke announced his candidacy for Minister-President in the upcoming vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] In response, an FDP spokesperson said that the FDP may not attend the vote, stating: "We reject both candidates and also don't wish to abstain.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] In which case our only remaining possibility is to not being physically present at the election." The leadership of the Young Union, the youth branch of the CDU, also announced its opposition to CDU support for either candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] However, the Thuringia CDU stated it intended to be present at the vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] On 4 March, Bodo Ramelow, who had changed his mind and had declared in the morning that the CDU should better abstain instead of supporting him, making the vote easier for them, was elected Minister-President by the Landtag after three rounds of voting.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] In the first two rounds, The Left, SPD, and Greens voted for Ramelow, while AfD voted for Höcke, the CDU abstained, and the FDP did not vote or abstain.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2019-thuringian-state-election] In the third round, Höcke withdrew, and Ramelow was elected with 43 in favour, 23 against, and 20 abstentions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The **2020 Thuringian government crisis**, also known as the **Thuringia crisis**, was triggered by the election of Thomas Kemmerich (FDP) as Thuringian Minister President with votes from the AfD, CDU and FDP on 5 February 2020.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The election attracted considerable national and international attention because, for the first time in the history of the Federal Republic of Germany, a Minister President was elected with votes from a far-right populist party, in this case the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] On 8 February 2020, Kemmerich resigned and served in an acting fashion until Bodo Ramelow was elected Minister President on 4 March 2020.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After Kemmerich's election, no members were appointed to the Bundesrat, and he himself also decided not to represent Thuringia there.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] For four weeks thereafter, the Thuringian State Government consisted only of the Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kemmerich was accused of neglecting participation in government business.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The crisis was also a consequence of the 2019 Thuringian state election, in which no established government coalition in Germany won a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Following Kemmerich's controversial election, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer stepped down as federal CDU leader, Mike Mohring withdrew as CDU state leader and parliamentary party leader in Thuringia, and Christian Hirte, Commissioner of the Federal Government for the New States, was dismissed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Before the October 2019 election, the Left party, led by Minister President Bodo Ramelow, was in power in a red-red-green coalition state government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After the election, the Left remained the strongest force in parliament, but the coalition no longer held an absolute majority of seats in parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The CDU and FDP proposed a so-called "Zimbabwe" coalition (black-red-yellow-green), but this also failed to gain a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Since none of the parties represented in the state parliament wanted to enter into negotiations with the AfD faction led by Björn Höcke, there was little prospect of a government coalition with a parliamentary majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The only theoretical majority alliances publicly discussed by at least one party were red-red-green plus FDP and a coalition of The Left with the CDU.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the run-up to the elections, the media also discussed the possibility that Bodo Ramelow could only continue to hold the office of Minister President in an acting fashion, without a new parliamentary election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Thuringian CDU showed internal disagreement after the state elections in 2019.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] While two members of the Landtag and some local politicians proposed a rapprochement with the AfD, others favored talks with the former Minister President Bodo Ramelow.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] These included Mike Mohring, the state chairman of the CDU in Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] At the end of October, he visited the federal chairwoman of the CDU, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, with the intention of meeting with Ramelow afterwards.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Already at the end of October, the FDP stated that it would not form a coalition with either the AfD or the Left Party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] A meeting between Ramelow and Mohring on 12 January 2020 yielded no new insights into how and whether the parliamentary opposition could support Ramelow, nor did a meeting between politicians from all state parliamentary factions except the AfD on 13 January 2020.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After the election, Minister President Bodo Ramelow declared that he, with the support of the Left Party, would fight for a continuation of the red-red-green coalition.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The three previous governing parties signed a government treaty on 4 February to continue the red-red-green alliance as a minority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The parties involved relied on situational parliamentary cooperation with the CDU and the FDP.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Left Party, the SPD and the Greens nominated the incumbent Minister President Bodo Ramelow as their candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The AfD faction proposed Christoph Kindervater, a largely unknown candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kindervater, the mayor of Sundhausen, had previously made his mark by writing a letter to the members of the CDU, FDP and AfD factions of parliament in order to run for the office of Minister President in Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He had run for the Unstrut-Hainich district council in 2019 on the CDU list and called himself a supporter of the Values Union.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The FDP faction decided to let their faction and state chairman Thomas Kemmerich run in the third ballot, if Bodo Ramelow failed twice before.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to their own statements, this was rather a symbolic candidacy to offer a "civic alternative" to the two candidates from left and right.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] However, they only wanted to run if the AfD also sent its own candidate in order to avoid receiving votes from the AfD, because they assumed that the AfD would vote for its own candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The day after the election, Kemmerich admitted in an interview in Heute Journal that the opposite should have been expected.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] However, the FDP ruled out cooperation or agreement with the AfD at any time.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] At the same time, there was no plan for the next steps in the formation of a government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the days leading up to the election, the press sometimes discussed the possibility "that a candidate from the CDU or FDP could win in the third round of voting with the support of the AfD".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Moreover, according to his own statements, nobody had expected that the AfD would not vote for its own candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to media reports, however, CDU federal chair Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer had asked FDP state leader Mohring and Lindner for Kemmerich not to run.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Thuringian constitution provides that in the first two rounds of voting, the Minister President is elected by an absolute majority of the members of the state parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] If this does not succeed, the third round of voting takes place.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In this round, the candidate with the most votes is considered elected.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Whether a Minister President with fewer yes votes than no votes can be elected is disputed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the first round of voting, Bodo Ramelow won 43 votes, one more than the Left, SPD and Greens had combined in seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Christoph Kindervater received 25 votes and thus at least three votes from outside the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This made a second round of voting necessary, as both candidates had missed the absolute majority of 46 votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the second round of voting, Ramelow received 44 votes and Kindervater 22 votes, which corresponded exactly to the number of AfD deputies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] 24 members of the Landtag abstained from voting.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] For the third round of voting which was necessary as a result, the AfD faction maintained Kindervater's candidacy, and in addition, as announced for this case, Thomas Kemmerich was nominated by the FDP faction.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kemmerich received 45 votes, Bodo Ramelow 44 and Kindervater 0 votes, one Member abstained.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kemmerich was thus elected the new Thuringian Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The result of the secret ballot shows that the AfD had apparently voted unanimously for Kemmerich despite Kindervater's candidacy being upheld, along with most of the FDP and CDU members of parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This tactical approach was later confirmed by the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kemmerich accepted the election without hesitation and was sworn in.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Later, Christian Lindner justified this by saying that Kemmerich had been "overwhelmed" by the situation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Immediately after the election, Kemmerich again ruled out any cooperation with the AfD and instead offered the CDU, SPD and Greens to form a non-partisan cabinet together.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] However, this was immediately rejected by them.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Instead, the previous red-red-green coalition gave him an ultimatum to resign.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Even together with the CDU, SPD and Greens, the FDP would have only had 39 of the 90 seats in the state parliament anyway.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kemmerich renounced the subsequently planned appointment of ministers and requested on behalf of the FDP faction that the state parliament session be adjourned indefinitely.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This was granted with the votes of AfD, CDU and FDP, against the votes of Left, SPD and Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The ministers of the acting Ramelow cabinet resigned from their posts when Kemmerich took office.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Since Kemmerich did not appoint any new ministers, he was the only member of the state government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The ministries were temporarily headed by the state secretaries appointed under Ramelow, and there were no cabinet meetings.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] No members were appointed to the Bundesrat, and no representative of Thuringia was present at one meeting of the Bundesrat.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Conference of Interior Ministers, which had been chaired by Georg Maier, Thuringia's Minister of the Interior, since the beginning of 2020, was temporarily returned to its previous chairman, Hans-Joachim Grote (Minister of the Interior of Schleswig-Holstein).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After the swearing-in, the leader of the Left parliamentary group, Susanne Hennig-Wellsow, refused to shake hands with Thomas Kemmerich and threw the bouquet of flowers intended for Ramelow at his feet.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] During his inaugural speech, the Left party shouted "charlatan" and "hypocrite" while demonstrators spontaneously gathered in front of the parliament building and the FDP party headquarters in Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Ramelow submitted a tweet on the day he was voted out of office, drawing parallels with the formation of the Baum-Frick government in Thuringia in 1930.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This tweet was controversially received, as it was illustrated by a photo of Höcke congratulating Kemmerich and of Hitler bowing to Reich President von Hindenburg on the so-called Day of Potsdam in 1933, and was deleted after a few days.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Stefan Möller, spokesman for the AfD Thuringia, said of the election process: "That was the whole point of the strategy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] So we tried to lure Mr Kemmerich onto the podium as the opposing candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Outside of Thuringia, Kemmerich's election initially met with spontaneous approval from right-wing groups, especially from the AfD, the conservative Values Union, and parts of the FDP.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Initially, the deputy federal chairman of the FDP, Wolfgang Kubicki, told the Deutsche Presse-Agentur that he was delighted that "a candidate from the democratic centre" had won, in view of the decision of the "majority of members in the Thuringian state parliament".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] However, the election results and Kemmerich's acceptance of the election soon caused a considerable stir nationwide, as well as criticism from top politicians, including the FDP.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Current and former leading FDP politicians such as Gerhart Baum, Marie-Agnes Strack-Zimmermann, Alexander Lambsdorff and Joachim Stamp demanded his immediate resignation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Christian Lindner also finally asked him to resign, describing it as a mistake "to have accepted an election under these conditions".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] CDU leader Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer said that cooperation with Kemmerich would be a violation of the party line that excludes any cooperation with the AfD, as he would not have been able to take office without their votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Chancellor Angela Merkel also spoke in connection with Kemmerich's election of an "unforgivable event" that would have to be reversed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] CSU leader Markus Söder, who called the election "unacceptable", and SPD leader Norbert Walter-Borjans, who called it a "scandal of the first order", expressed similar sentiments.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The reactions of the Thuringian CDU members of the Landtag varied widely.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In response to the question "Why did you do this?" which was asked by *Die Zeit*, most of them stated afterwards that they had given their vote to Kemmerich as the "candidate of the middle".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] One CDU member, Raymond Walk, commented that they had not expected "that the AfD would sacrifice its own candidates in such cold blood".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Another, Beate Meißner, said: "I cannot say that I would be happy about Kemmerich's election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] However, I could not have expected the AfD to behave in this way.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Neither would I have trusted them with so much perfidiousness in parliament to put up a sham candidate, nor would I have believed that they would act so cohesively.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Other CDU members of the Landtag, such as Jörg Kellner and Michael Heym, do not regret in retrospect either that they elected Kemmerich or that he accepted the election, but deplore his resignation, for which they blame the pressure from federal politics.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Wolfgang Schäuble (CDU), President of the Bundestag, criticized the events in Erfurt and the reaction of federal politics to the election of the Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] "The way in which elections, as with elected members of parliament, the election of a prime minister, i.e. a constitutional body, has been dealt with is not appropriate in our parliamentary democracy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The role of the AfD would be significantly enhanced by this "coup", said political scientist Uwe Jun.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The political scientist Hajo Funke considered the events to be a "breach of taboo", but did not see a "breach of the dam;" rather, due to the outraged reactions of many people, the dam had become even higher.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to Funke, "the AfD has moved even further away from a perspective of power." According to the historian Volker Weiß, the AfD votes for an FDP Minister President were irritating at first glance, but Mr.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Höcke is trying to "change his image" and wants to "offer himself as a serious partner".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Regarding the debates about a possible toleration of a government by the AfD, the political scientist Albrecht von Lucke said that the Union was thereby promoting precisely a "civicization strategy" of the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This would "brilliantly conceal the increasing radicalisation of the party." The historian Winfried Süß called the events "devastating" and Kemmerich's behaviour "history-forgotten." The strong political polarization reminded Süß of the conditions at the end of the Weimar Republic.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Jena political scientist Torsten Oppelland, on the other hand, saw the election as largely unproblematic.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He explained that an election by the AfD did not have to mean any further cooperation with it, and that the Greens and the SPD had a duty to cooperate with Kemmerich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Dresden political scientist Werner J.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to Guido Bohsem, the real aim of the AfD is "the destruction of the established".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Josef Schuster, President of the Central Council of Jews in Germany, was "appalled" by the election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He said that "the FDP is thus leaving the consensus of the democratic parties." Christoph Heubner of the International Auschwitz Committee spoke of a "breaking of the dam and taboo in Germany".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The fact that "precisely this right-wing extremist Höcke-AfD has so easily managed to present the democratic parties as incapable of consensus is a political disaster with far-reaching consequences," said Heubner.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Demonstrations against the election of Kemmerich on the same day, called by the parties The Left, SPD and the Greens as well as other organizations, brought together several thousand people in at least 15 German cities, 6 of them in Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] There were also demonstrations in the following days.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] These events led to the cancellation of the "Regional Conference German Sustainability Strategy 2020" in Erfurt.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Since his election as Minister President, Kemmerich has been exposed to organized "hatred in the form of threatening letters and mass mailings," according to the FDP state executive board.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] A "direct and immediate threat" has led to the fact that, in addition to the usual personal protection for the Minister President, his home and children are now also protected.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In numerous other places throughout Germany, FDP politicians also faced massive threats and attacks as a result of the election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Several party headquarters of the FDP were graffitied with slogans and damaged.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In some cases, police protection had to be provided.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The interior politician Konstantin Kuhle spoke of an "absolute escalation." The NRW headquarters of the CDU in Düsseldorf was also vandalized.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] On 6 February 2020, the day after the election, Christian Lindner went to Thuringia to persuade Thomas Kemmerich to resign, which he also tied to continuing his own office as party chairman.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Thereupon, Thomas Kemmerich announced his resignation at a press conference on the same day.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The FDP parliamentary group announced that it would support a motion to dissolve the parliament under Article 50 of the state constitution.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Should this motion be unsuccessful, Kemmerich announced a vote of confidence under Article 74 of the Thuringian state constitution, which would have cleared the way for a new election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After the coalition committee of the CDU, CSU and SPD in the federal government, in consultation with the FDP, also demanded his immediate resignation on February 8, Kemmerich resigned on the same day with immediate effect.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] However, he remained in office as acting Minister President until the election of a new Minister President on March 4.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Kemmerich also announced that he would waive his salary as Minister President and the transitional allowance to be paid at the end of his term of office.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This would have amounted to at least 93,000 euros in total.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] If this was not possible, he said, he would donate anything beyond his parliamentary salary to Thuringian organizations, such as the Association of Victims of Stalinism or the Arbeitsgemeinschaft zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] When criticism was voiced that former AfD members were also active in the former association, he withdrew his announcement in this regard.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After Bodo Ramelow was re-elected as his successor, it was clear that the total payments (including transitional allowance and payment for the whole of March) to Kemmerich would amount to approximately 110,000 euros.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the CDU, the electoral behaviour of the Thuringian state association made the internal party differences in dealing with the AfD particularly clear.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] CDU state chairman Mike Mohring had initially defended the election of Thomas Kemmerich despite massive criticism.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After a visit by the CDU presidium in Erfurt, he announced his resignation as CDU faction chair.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] It was not known whether Mohring actively supported Kemmerich's election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] On 2 March 2020, Mario Voigt was elected the new parliamentary party leader of the CDU Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Mohring also relinquished the chairmanship of the state CDU association.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Federal Government Commissioner for the New States, Christian Hirte (CDU), who had congratulated Kemmerich on his election via Twitter, asked for his dismissal as Parliamentary State Secretary on 8 February 2020 on the advice of the Chancellor.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer announced her resignation from the office of federal CDU chairwoman on February 10, saying that the decision had "matured some time ago".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Most media also saw the resignation as the result of a longer development.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] On 7 February, the Federal Chairman Christian Lindner asked the Federal Executive Board for a vote of confidence.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He had been exposed to ongoing criticism of his reaction to the election of the Minister President because he had initially welcomed the acceptance of the election by FDP candidate Kemmerich despite the apparent support of AfD members of parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In a statement, he then admitted that Kemmerich's candidacy had already been a mistake.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The FDP board expressed its confidence in Lindner.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Immediately after Thomas Kemmerich's election as Minister President, opinion research institutes in Thuringia conducted election polls which revealed clear shifts in favor of the Left and losses of the CDU.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to several polls, the FDP, which had barely reached the five percent hurdle in the state election, would only get four percent and would no longer be represented in the state parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] One possible way out of the government crisis was to dissolve parliament and hold new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to Article 50 of the Thuringian State Constitution, one third of the members of the Landtag should have submitted a motion to this effect and a two-thirds majority should have approved it.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] New elections were demanded, for example, by the black-red coalition at federal level.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] After a meeting of the coalition committee chaired by Angela Merkel on 8 February 2020, the federal chairmen Norbert Walter-Borjans, Saskia Esken (both SPD), Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer (CDU) and Markus Söder (CSU) called for new elections to the Thuringian state parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] It is a novelty in German politics that the leaders of the parties involved in the federal government have called for the election of a new state parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In connection with Kemmerich's announcement of his resignation, the FDP faction at state level announced that it would support a motion to dissolve parliament under Article 50 of the state constitution.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The CDU faction in the state parliament, however, was critical of new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Another point of criticism in new elections was the long period of time until a new government was formed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Thuringia's state constitution stipulates that new elections must be held within 70 days of the dissolution of the state parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Since Kemmerich is now only acting Minister President, he would not have been able to ask for a vote of confidence or appoint ministers during that time.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] According to the Thuringian state constitution, it is not possible to dissolve the state parliament by referendum, as is the case in Berlin, for example.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The election of a new Minister President could replace Thomas Kemmerich in the office of Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] To this end, a constructive vote of no confidence was initially considered by the Left Party, the SPD and the Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] With Kemmerich's resignation, a normal election became possible.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Several candidates were considered for this.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Left, SPD, and Greens wanted to elect Bodo Ramelow as Minister President, as originally planned.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] As in the election on 5 February 2020, they would have needed four additional votes from the CDU or FDP to do so.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Alexander Gauland, leader of the AfD faction in the Bundestag, recommended that the Thuringian AfD faction elect Mr.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The parliamentary group of the Left party in the state parliament rejected a candidacy of Ramelow if there was no firm promise from the CDU or FDP to support the candidacy with the necessary votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This was offset by calls for another candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Both variants met with rejection from the Left, SPD and the Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Jacques Schuster, the chief commentator for *Die Welt*, welcomed the proposal, commenting that Bodo Ramelow's attempt to form a red-red-green government led by the Left party, despite the lack of a parliamentary majority, was the real core of the problem.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Karin Prien and Daniel Günther (CDU), on the other hand, saw the CDU's symmetrical distancing from the Left and AfD as "the root of the evil." Cooperation with the Left party should not be ruled out.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Finn Rütten commented in Stern that equating the AfD and the Left Party (horseshoe theory) would in no way do justice to the situation in Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Rütten's opinion was that while Björn Höcke was spreading nationalistic ideas and was only satisfied with the absolute majority, the Left Party had been showing for decades that it was involved in shaping democratic, responsible policies when it came to participation in government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Party researcher Michael Lühmann interpreted the cultivation of sweeping hostility towards the Left as a "life lie" of the east-german CDU, in order to distract from its own past as a bloc party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] On 17 February 2020, representatives of the Left, SPD, Greens and CDU met for the first time for negotiations with the aim of finding a joint solution to avert the "incipient state crisis" (Ramelow quote).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Bodo Ramelow proposed a solution in this round in which new elections and the election of a new Minister President would be directly linked.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The state parliament should decide on its own dissolution, and at the same time elect Christine Lieberknecht (CDU) as Minister President for the legislative period remaining until the new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He also suggested that Lieberknecht should form a "technical" government in which three key ministries would be reappointed: the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Finance, and the State Chancellery.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Christine Lieberknecht had gained respect across party lines during her time as President of the Landtag (1999-2004) and has relevant government experience as former Minister President of Thuringia (from 2009 to 2014).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The CDU Thuringia rejected this and suggested that Lieberknecht should remain in office longer than Ramelow had intended and lead a full cabinet of experts.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Lieberknecht thereupon withdrew her willingness to run as interim minister president and announced that she had only wanted to accept Ramelow's proposal for a solution with quick new elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This "contradiction with the CDU" could "not be resolved." In Lieberknecht's opinion, true political stability in the Thuringian parliament could only be achieved by recognizing the real majority situation and by agreeing on reliable parliamentary cooperation between the CDU and the Left.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] On 21 February 2020, the Left Party, SPD, Greens and CDU agreed on measures to overcome the government crisis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] This was in response to the CDU's request for a postponement of the new elections, as well as to the Red-Red-Green's plan to temporarily re-elect Ramelow as Minister-President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The cooperation of the four parties provided for Bodo Ramelow to be elected Minister President on 4 March 2020 and to lead a minority government of Left, SPD, and Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In return, it was agreed that new elections to the Landtag would not take place until 25 April 2021.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] A so-called "stability mechanism" was to ensure a functioning government during this period: the CDU undertook to coordinate all motions in the state parliament with the government parties beforehand in order to rule out that CDU, FDP and AfD together block the government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] At the same time, the Left, SPD, and Greens were also to come to an agreement with the CDU in advance on plans.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The state budget for 2021 should also be drawn up in this way.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Both with this agreement, and with Kemmerich's election previously, which was a cooperation with the AfD, the CDU Thuringia violated an incompatibility decision of the federal party, which excluded any cooperation with the Left and AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The federal level of the CDU therefore rejected the compromise.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Left, SPD and Greens nominated Bodo Ramelow as candidate, as stated in the agreement reached with the CDU.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Two days before the election of the Minister President, the AfD declared that its parliamentary group leader Björn Höcke would run against Ramelow.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The FDP faction announced it would boycott the election to make it clear that they reject both candidates (Ramelow and Höcke).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] As in the election for Minister President in February 2020, the Thuringian constitution provides that in the first two rounds of voting, the Minister President is elected by an absolute majority of the members of the state parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] If this is not successful, the third round of voting takes place.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In both the first and second rounds of voting on 4 March 2020, Bodo Ramelow received 42 votes, which should have come from the parliamentary groups of the Left, SPD and Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Björn Höcke received 22 votes, which corresponded to the parliamentary strength of the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The 21 abstentions in each case were to be attributed to the CDU faction.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The FDP was present at the election, but did not vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the third round of voting, the AfD parliamentary group withdrew the candidacy of Björn Höcke, leaving Bodo Ramelow as the only remaining candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Ramelow received 42 votes in favour, 23 against and 20 abstentions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He was thus re-elected Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In his inaugural speech, Ramelow expressed his pleasure at the end of the government crisis, thanked the CDU in particular for concluding the stability pact, and called on the parliamentary groups in the state parliament to cooperate constructively.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He sharply criticized the AfD for setting a trap for the FDP and CDU, accusing them of not respecting the parliament and democracy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He also justified it by saying that he had refused to shake hands with Björn Höcke, who wanted to congratulate him.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He said that he would only shake his hand if Mr.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Höcke stopped "trampling democracy underfoot" and instead defended it.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The General Secretary of the SPD, Lars Klingbeil, expressed his relief about the election of Ramelow.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He wrote on Twitter: "The chaos in Thuringia has come to an end for the time being.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The AfD, on the other hand, expressed criticism.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Federal spokesman Jörg Meuthen accused CDU and FDP of having helped a Left politician into office by abstaining or not participating in the debate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The FDP, on the other hand, emphasized that by refusing to participate in the election, they had expressed their rejection of both candidates.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Björn Höcke criticized that the new Minister President had shown lack of manner by refusing to shake hands.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] He had wanted to show Ramelow that he accepted his democratic election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The Landtag election scheduled for 25 April 2021, based on the stability pact, was initially postponed to 26 September 2021, due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The governing parliamentary groups of the Left, SPD and Greens declared that they would not make any further attempt to dissolve the Landtag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] A few days later, the AfD parliamentary group in the Thuringian state parliament filed a motion of no confidence against Ramelow and proposed Björn Höcke as the new Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] In the vote on 23 July 2021, 22 deputies voted for the motion and 46 against.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] The CDU parliamentary group had previously announced that it would not participate in the secret ballot and remained seated in the chamber.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2020-thuringian-government-crisis] Because the motion was rejected, Ramelow remained Thuringia's Minister President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The **2024 Thuringian state election** was held on 1 September 2024 to elect the members of the 8th Landtag of Thuringia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] It was held on the same day as the 2024 Saxony state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The outgoing government was a minority government formed by The Left, the Social Democratic Party (SPD), and The Greens, led by Minister-President Bodo Ramelow of The Left.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Ramelow had led the state since 2014, including through the political crisis following the 2020 state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) emerged as the largest party with 33% of the vote, marking its best ever result and the first time it placed first in a state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The governing coalition suffered heavy losses: The Left lost more than half its support and fell to fourth place with 13%, while the SPD recorded its worst result in any postwar state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Greens and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) both failed to clear the five percent threshold and lost all of their seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) saw modest gains, placing second with 24%, while the newly-formed Sahra Wagenknecht Alliance (BSW) debuted in third with 16%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The election marked a historic breakthrough for the AfD, which became the first far-right party since the Nazi Party (NSDAP) to win a plurality in a German state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] According to the Thuringian Constitution, an early election may be held if, at the request of one-third of its members, the Landtag votes with a two-thirds majority to dissolve itself.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] This may also occur if the Landtag does not vote confidence in a Minister-President within three weeks of a failed vote of confidence in the incumbent.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The motion to dissolve the Landtag may only be voted on between eleven and thirty days after its submission.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] If passed, the election must then take place within 70 days.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In the aftermath of the 2020 Thuringian government crisis, The Left, CDU, SPD, and Greens came to an agreement to dissolve the Landtag and schedule a new election for 25 April 2021.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] At the time the four parties held a combined 63 of the 90 seats, two more than the 61 votes required for a dissolution.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] That January, the four parties agreed to postpone the election to 26 September 2021, the same date as the upcoming federal election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The vote to dissolve the Landtag was scheduled for 19 July 2021.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] However, the motion was withdrawn on 16 July after four CDU and two Left members informed party leaders they would vote against it, leaving it clearly short of the required majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Left parliamentary leader Stefan Dittes announced there would not be another effort to dissolve the Landtag, and the red-red-green minority government continued for a full term.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In the previous state election held on 27 October 2019, The Left became the largest party for the first time in any German state, winning 31.0% of votes cast.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) made the largest gains, increasing its vote share by almost 13 percentage points and became the second largest party with 23.4%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), which had previously been the largest party in the Landtag, lost almost 12 points and fell to third place with 21.7%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) placed fourth on 8.2%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Greens narrowly retained their position in the legislature, winning 5.2% of votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Free Democratic (FDP) entered the Landtag for the first time since 2009, exceeding the 5% electoral threshold by just 73 votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Incumbent Minister President Bodo Ramelow of The Left had led a coalition government of The Left, SPD, and Greens since 2014.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Left's gains were offset by losses for the SPD and Greens, and the coalition lost its majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The loss of a majority for the Ramelow's red-red-green coalition led to an unclear path to a new government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The state constitution provides that a Minister-President is elected with a plurality of votes if two rounds of balloting fails to produce a majority, allowing the coalition to potentially continue as a minority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Unexpectedly, the FDP leader Thomas Kemmerich was elected as Minister-President on this third ballot, with 45 votes to Ramelow's 44.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Kemmerich was elected with the support of the FDP, CDU, and controversially, the AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] This was the first time AfD had been involved in the election of a head of state government in Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The apparent cooperation of the three parties was viewed by some as breaking the *cordon sanitaire* around AfD which had been in place since its formation, in which all other parties sought to deny AfD government or political influence, refusing to negotiate or work with them on any level.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] This sparked major controversy nationwide, with many politicians expressing their outrage, including federal Chancellor and former CDU leader Angela Merkel, who described it as "unforgivable" and condemned her party's involvement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Kemmerich announced his resignation on 6 February, just a day after taking office.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] He remained in office in an interim capacity.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In the re-ran vote a month later, Ramelow was re-elected Minister-President.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] On 15 June 2020, the SPD elected Georg Maier as state chairman and lead candidate for the planned 2021 election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] This came after previous leader Wolfgang Tiefensee resigned his position.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In September 2020, former Federal Commissioner for the New States Christian Hirte was elected as state CDU chairman, succeeding Mike Mohring, who had resigned during the government crisis in February.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] On 17 November, the state executive nominated parliamentary group leader Mario Voigt as their preferred lead candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] After extended pressure from the federal FDP as well as other state branches, Thomas Kemmerich announced on 11 December that he was ineligible as his party's lead candidate in the planned 2021 election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] This was the first time the AfD has won the plurality of seats in a state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Chancellor Olaf Scholz called on other political parties to prevent the AfD from governing by upholding a "firewall" against them.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Though a CDU-AfD coalition would have a majority, all other parties have ruled out forming a coalition with the party and its Thuringian leader, Björn Höcke, due to their extremist tendencies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The State Office for Protection of the Constitution classifies the Thuringian AfD as a right-wing extremist organisation, and Höcke has been found guilty of using the forbidden Nazi slogan "*Everything for Germany*".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The CDU has historically declined to collaborate with Die Linke (The Left), though a coalition with BSW, also a radical leftist party, was also considered unappealing by party members.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In the aftermath to the elections in both Thuringia and Saxony, Sahra Wagenknecht, leader of the BSW, stated her preferences to go into a coalition with either the CDU and/or the SPD in an interview with ARD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The office of President of the Landtag, the body's presiding officer, is traditionally reserved for the largest party in parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] However, the four other parties all rejected the possibility of the AfD holding this position given its classification as an extremist party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In addition, AfD made known its candidate for President would be its MdL Wiebke Muhsal, who was convicted and fined for defrauding the Landtag administration in 2015.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The other parties saw this as a deliberate provocation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] To avoid a potential scenario where a President of the Landtag would be elected with AfD votes, or that of a deadlock with AfD candidates repeatedly being voted down, CDU and BSW jointly proposed changing the election procedure at the first sitting on the 26 of September.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The election requires a simple majority, and under the rule then in effect the largest party had the right of nomination (*Vorschlagsrecht*).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The new proposal was to allow all parties to nominate candidates from the outset.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] CDU put forward as a consensus candidate its MdL Thadäus König, who received the highest share of constituency votes of any candidate in the election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The other parties indicated they would support him.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] He also gave an openly political speech, which was seen as a breach of decorum.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The other parties, in particular CDU parliamentary leader Andreas Bühl, accused Treutler of not acting in a non-partisan manner, with Bühl angrily condemning what he called "a seizure of power" during the contentious session.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The sitting was abandoned and CDU, supported by other parties, filed an emergency complaint with the Thuringian Constitutional Court in response.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Treutler then filed a countercomplaint on 27 September, asking the court to dismiss the CDU complaint as inadmissible.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In the late hours of 27 September, the court ruled unanimously in favor of CDU's complaint.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] It held that there was no exclusive right for the largest parliamentary group to propose candidates for the office of President of the Landtag, and thus that amending the voting procedure was permissible.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The court also confirmed that members have the right to debate and amend the rules before the election of a President of the Landtag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Treutler was thus required to put the motion to a vote at the reconstituted sitting on 28 September, which passed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The CDU candidate König was then elected president with 54 votes to 32 for Muhsal.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In response to this crisis, König advocated for changing the definition of father of the house from the member with the oldest physical age to that with the longest tenure of service; this definition is already used in the federal Bundestag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] *Die Welt* noted that Treutler had been substituted for a unanimously nominated constituency candidate relatively close to the election, and speculated that it was to ensure the party would supply the father of the house.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] When the paper asked Höcke about this, he simply replied "you can be sure that we at AfD Thuringia have very far-reaching strategic planning".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The day after the election, the CDU executive voted unanimously to seek exploratory talks with the BSW and SPD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] BSW leader Katja Wolf stated that federal leader Sahra Wagenknecht would be attending these initial discussions to "stand up for war and peace issues," but would not be involved in further negotiations.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Bodo Ramelow and The Left called for the CDU to "act responsibly and find a majority among democratic parties".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] They also denied rumours that Left party deputies could defect to the BSW to provide the prospective government with a parliamentary majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In a speech on 20 September, federal CDU leader Friedrich Merz described a coalition including BSW in either Thuringia or Saxony as "very, very, very unlikely".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Nevertheless, exploratory talks for a CDU-BSW-SPD coalition, the so-called “blackberry coalition", began on 30 September.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] This minority government is still one seat short of a majority, requiring support or abstentions from The Left to conduct business.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] On 17 October, *Die Welt* reported that exploratory talks had concluded and a preliminary distribution of ministries had taken place.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] There was still no conclusion as to how to achieve a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] CDU and SPD confirmed the talks had finished, but described the material leaked to *Die Welt* as "fake".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] On 25 October, amid reports that talks were stalling, Wagenknecht was heavily criticized for personally vetoing compromise foreign policy language that was to be inserted into the preamble of a report on the exploratory talks.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In an interview with ARD, Merz accused Wagenknecht of "wanting to run a federal election campaign where she constantly says no" instead of attempting to lead, and that his party would not compromise on NATO membership and aid to Ukraine.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Though BSW state leaders expressed their desire to continue, SPD state leader Maier told MDR that he had little hope that coalition talks could succeed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Despite this, after a pause in talks over the following weekend, the party leaders announced they had reached a consensus on foreign policy issues and decided to begin formal coalition negotiations.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] A completed draft coalition agreement was presented in the Landtag on 22 November.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] In the first week of December, the CDU party executive approved it with 37 out of 38 votes in favor.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] BSW submitted it to its full state membership – which at the time was 126 people – and it was approved with 76 votes in favor to 28 against; Wagenknecht had also endorsed ratification of the agreement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] SPD also submitted the agreement to its full membership for a vote, which despite a campaign against ratification by the state Jusos saw 68 per cent of the roughly 1,700 votes in favor.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The election of a Minister-President was scheduled for 12 December.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Left conditioned any votes for Voigt on a written agreement formalizing relations between itself and the coalition, in particular the stipulation that the Minister-President vote as well as legislative compromises only involve those four parties "to avoid the potential for blackmail" from AfD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] As the national CDU has passed a "resolution of incompatibility" regarding The Left and AfD, which prohibits any formal agreements with either party, Voigt has not agreed to this.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] The Left, however, noted that such a "stability pact" had been signed with the CDU after the 2020 government crisis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Shortly before the election, Left parliamentary leader Christian Schaft posted on X that several of his bloc's members intended to vote for Voigt, though he cautioned that "our votes are an advance of trust, not a blank check".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/2024-thuringian-state-election] Voigt was elected Minister-President on the first ballot with 51 votes in favor, 33 votes against, and 4 abstentions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was born in Braunau am Inn in Austria-Hungary and moved to Germany in 1913.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He was decorated during his service in the German Army in the First World War, receiving the Iron Cross.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1919, he joined the German Workers' Party (DAP), the precursor of the Nazi Party, and in 1921, was appointed the leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, he attempted to seize governmental power in a failed coup in Munich and was sentenced to five years in prison, serving just over a year.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, he dictated the first volume of his autobiography and political manifesto *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] After his early release in 1924, he gained popular support by attacking the Treaty of Versailles as well as promoting pan-Germanism, antisemitism, and anti-communism with charismatic oratory and Nazi propaganda.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He frequently denounced communism as being part of an international Jewish conspiracy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] By November 1932, the Nazi Party held the most seats in the *Reichstag*, but not a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Former chancellor Franz von Papen and other conservative politicians convinced President Paul von Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly thereafter, on 23 March, the *Reichstag* passed the Enabling Act of 1933, which ultimately began the Weimar Republic's transformation into Nazi Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Upon Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler replaced him as head of state and thereafter transformed Germany into a totalitarian dictatorship.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Domestically, Hitler implemented numerous racist policies and sought to deport or kill German Jews.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His first six years in power resulted in rapid economic recovery from the Great Depression, the abrogation of restrictions imposed on Germany after the First World War, and the annexation of territories inhabited by millions of ethnic Germans, which initially gave him significant popular support.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] One of Hitler's key goals was *Lebensraum* (lit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] 'living space') for the German people in Eastern Europe.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His aggressive, expansionist foreign policy is considered the primary cause of World War II in Europe.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 September 1939, Hitler oversaw the German invasion of Poland, thereby causing Britain and France to declare war on Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] After ordering an invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, he declared war on the United States in December of the same year.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of 1941, German forces and the European Axis powers occupied most of Europe and North Africa.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] These gains were gradually reversed after 1941 until the Allied forces defeated the German military in 1945.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 29 April 1945, Hitler married his longtime partner, Eva Braun, in the *Führerbunker* in Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] They committed suicide the next day to avoid capture by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The historian and biographer Ian Kershaw described Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Under Hitler's leadership and racist ideology, the Nazi regime was responsible for the genocide of an estimated six million Jews and millions of other victims, whom he and his followers deemed *Untermenschen* (lit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazis were also responsible for the deliberate killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of civilians killed during World War II was unprecedented in warfare, and the casualties make it the deadliest conflict in history.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's father, Alois Hitler, was the illegitimate child of Maria Schicklgruber.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The baptismal register did not show the name of his father, and Alois initially bore his mother's surname, "Schicklgruber".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1842, Johann Georg Hiedler married Alois's mother.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was brought up in the family of Hiedler's brother, Johann Nepomuk Hiedler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois worked as a civil servant from 1855 until his retirement in 1895.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1876, Alois was made legitimate and his baptismal record annotated by a priest to register Johann Georg Hiedler as Alois's father (recorded as "Georg Hitler").
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois then assumed the surname "Hitler", also spelled "Hiedler", "Hüttler", or "Huettler".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The name is probably based on the German word *Hütte* (lit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] 'hut'), and has the meaning "one who lives in a hut".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi official Hans Frank suggested that Alois's mother had been employed as a housekeeper by a Jewish family in Graz, and that the family's 19-year-old son Leopold Frankenberger had fathered Alois, a claim that came to be known as the Frankenberger thesis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] No Frankenberger was registered in Graz during that period, and no record has been produced of a Leopold Frankenberger's existence, so historians dismiss the claim that Alois's father was Jewish.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 2025, blood from the sofa in Hitler's study was used by Turi King of the University of Bath for DNA analysis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The blood was confirmed to be Hitler's by comparing it to that of a male-line relative, and the DNA analysis also showed that Hitler did not have Jewish ancestry through his father.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] "If that was the case, we wouldn't have got the DNA match with him," King said.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Adolf Hitler was born on 20 April 1889 in Braunau am Inn, a town in Austria-Hungary (present-day Austria), close to the border with Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He was the fourth of six children born to Alois Hitler and his third wife, Klara Pölzl.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Three of Hitler's siblings—Gustav, Ida, and Otto—died in infancy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Also living in the household were Alois's children from his second marriage: Alois Jr.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1892, the family moved to Passau, Germany, following Alois's promotion to the customs administration in Passau.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was promoted and transferred to Linz, Austria, on 1 April 1893, but the rest of the family remained in Passau.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] There, Hitler acquired the distinctive lower Bavarian dialect, rather than Austrian German, which marked his speech throughout his life.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The family returned to Austria and settled in Leonding on 9 May 1894, and in June 1895, Alois retired to Hafeld, near Lambach, where he farmed and kept bees.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler attended *Volksschule* (a state-funded primary school) in nearby Fischlham.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The move to Hafeld coincided with the onset of intense father–son conflicts caused by six-year-old Hitler's refusal to conform to the strict discipline of his school.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois tried to browbeat his son into obedience, while Adolf did his best to be the opposite of whatever his father wanted.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois would also beat his son, although his mother tried to protect him from regular beatings.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois Hitler's farming efforts at Hafeld were unsuccessful, and in 1897, the family moved to Lambach.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The eight-year-old Hitler took singing lessons, sang in the church choir, and even considered becoming a priest.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1898, the family returned permanently to Leonding.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was deeply affected by the death of his younger brother Edmund in 1900 from measles.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler transformed from a confident, outgoing, and conscientious student to a morose, detached boy who frequently clashed with his father and teachers.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Paula Hitler recalled that Adolf was a teenage bully who would often slap her.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois had made a successful career in the customs bureau and wanted his son to follow in his footsteps.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later dramatised an episode from this period when his father took him to visit a customs office, depicting it as an event that gave rise to an unforgiving antagonism between father and son, who were both strong-willed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Ignoring his son's desire to attend a classical high school and become an artist, Alois sent Hitler to the *Realschule* in Linz in September 1900.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler rebelled against this decision, and in *Mein Kampf* states that he intentionally performed poorly in school, hoping that once his father saw "what little progress I was making at the technical school he would let me devote myself to my dream".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Like many Austrian Germans, Hitler began to develop German nationalist ideas from a young age.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He expressed loyalty only to Germany, despising the declining Habsburg monarchy and its rule over an ethnically diverse empire.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and his friends used the greeting "Heil", and sang the "Deutschlandlied" instead of the Austrian Imperial anthem.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] After Alois's sudden death on 3 January 1903, Hitler's performance at school deteriorated, and his mother allowed him to leave.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He enrolled at the *Realschule* in Steyr in September 1904, where his behaviour and performance improved.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1905, after passing a repeat of the final exam, Hitler left the school without any ambitions for further education or clear plans for a career.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1907, Hitler left Linz to live and study fine art in Vienna, financed by an orphan's benefits and support from his mother.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He applied for admission to the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna but was rejected twice.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The director suggested Hitler should apply to the School of Architecture, but he lacked the necessary academic credentials because he had not finished secondary school.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 December 1907, his mother died of breast cancer at the age of 47; Hitler was 18 at the time.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1909, Hitler ran out of money and was forced to live a bohemian life in homeless shelters and the Meldemannstraße dormitory.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He earned money as a casual labourer and by painting and selling watercolours of Vienna's sights.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] During his time in Vienna, he pursued a growing passion for architecture and music, attending ten performances of *Lohengrin*, his favourite of Richard Wagner's operas.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In Vienna, Hitler was first exposed to racist rhetoric.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Populists such as mayor Karl Lueger exploited the city's prevalent antisemitic sentiment, occasionally also espousing German nationalist notions for political benefit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] German nationalism was especially widespread in the Mariahilf district, where Hitler then lived.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Georg Ritter von Schönerer became a major influence on Hitler, and he developed an admiration for Martin Luther.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler read newspapers and pamphlets that promoted prejudice and warned of an influx of Eastern European Jews, as well as writings by figures such as Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, Gustave Le Bon, and Arthur Schopenhauer.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] During his years in Vienna he also developed strong anti-Slavic sentiments.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The origin and development of Hitler's antisemitism remain a matter of debate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His friend August Kubizek claimed that Hitler was a "confirmed antisemite" before he left Linz.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] However, the historian Brigitte Hamann describes Kubizek's claim as "problematical".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler states in *Mein Kampf* that he first became an antisemite in Vienna, Reinhold Hanisch, who helped him to sell his paintings, disagrees.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sold some of his art through a Jewish businessman named Samuel Morgenstern while living in Vienna.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of Morgenstern's clients were Jewish; for example, a lawyer named Josef Feingold purchased several of Hitler's paintings of Vienna's historical architecture.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Evans states that "historians now generally agree that his notorious, murderous antisemitism emerged well after Germany's defeat in World War I, as a product of the paranoid "stab-in-the-back" explanation for the catastrophe".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler received the final part of his father's estate in May 1913 and moved to Munich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] When he was conscripted into the Austro-Hungarian Army, he journeyed to Salzburg on 5 February 1914 for medical assessment.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] After he was deemed unfit for service, he returned to Munich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later claimed that he did not wish to serve the Habsburg Empire because of the mixture of races in its army and his belief that the collapse of Austria-Hungary was imminent.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Hitler was living in Munich and voluntarily enlisted in the Bavarian Army.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] According to a 1924 report by the Bavarian authorities, allowing Hitler to serve was most likely an administrative error, because as an Austrian citizen, he should have been returned to Austria.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Posted to the Bavarian Reserve Infantry Regiment 16 (1st Company of the List Regiment), he served as a dispatch runner on the Western Front in France and Belgium, spending nearly half his time at the regimental headquarters in Fournes-en-Weppes, well behind the front lines.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1914, he was present at the First Battle of Ypres and in that year was decorated for bravery, receiving the Iron Cross, Second Class.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] During the war, he was saved by his commanding officer, Fritz Wiedemann, who pulled Hitler out of the rubble of a collapsed building while under heavy fire.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] During his service at headquarters, Hitler pursued his artistic interests, drawing cartoons and providing instructions for an army newspaper.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] During the Battle of the Somme in October 1916, he was wounded in the left thigh when a shell exploded in the dispatch runners' dugout.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler spent almost two months recovering in hospital at Beelitz, returning to his regiment on 5 March 1917.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He was present at the Battle of Arras of 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He received the black Wound Badge on 18 May 1918.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Three months later, in August 1918, on a recommendation by Lieutenant Hugo Gutmann, his Jewish superior, Hitler received the Iron Cross, First Class, a decoration rarely awarded at Hitler's *Gefreiter* rank.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 15 October 1918, he was temporarily blinded in a mustard gas attack and was hospitalised in Pasewalk.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, Hitler learned of Germany's defeat, and, by his own account, suffered a second bout of blindness after receiving this news.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler described his role in World War I as "the greatest of all experiences" and was praised by his commanding officers for his bravery.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His wartime experience reinforced his German patriotism, and he was shocked by Germany's capitulation in November 1918.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His displeasure with the collapse of the war effort began to shape his ideology.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Treaty of Versailles stipulated that Germany had to relinquish several of its territories and demilitarise the Rhineland.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The treaty imposed economic sanctions and levied heavy reparations on the country.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Many Germans saw the treaty as an unjust humiliation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] They especially objected to Article 231, which they interpreted as declaring Germany responsible for the war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Versailles Treaty and the economic, social, and political conditions in Germany after the war were later exploited by Hitler for political gain.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] After the war, Hitler returned to Munich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Without formal education or career prospects, he remained in the army.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In July 1919, he was appointed *Verbindungsmann* (intelligence agent) of an *Aufklärungskommando* (reconnaissance unit) of the *Reichswehr*, assigned to influence other soldiers and to infiltrate the German Workers' Party (DAP).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At a DAP meeting on 12 September 1919, Party chairman Anton Drexler was impressed by Hitler's oratorical skills.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He gave him a copy of his pamphlet *My Political Awakening*, which contained antisemitic, nationalist, anti-capitalist, and anti-Marxist ideas.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On the orders of his army superiors, Hitler applied to join the party, and within a week was accepted as party member 555 (the party began counting membership at 500 to give the impression they were a much larger party).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made his earliest known written statement about the Jewish question in a 16 September 1919 letter to Adolf Gemlich (now known as the Gemlich letter).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In the letter, Hitler argues that the aim of the government "must unshakably be the removal of the Jews altogether".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At the DAP, Hitler met Dietrich Eckart, one of the party's founders and a member of the occult Thule Society.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Eckart became Hitler's mentor, exchanging ideas with him and introducing him to a wide range of Munich society.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] To increase its appeal, the DAP changed its name to the *Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei* (National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP), now known as the "Nazi Party").
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler designed the party's banner of a swastika in a white circle on a red background.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was discharged from the army on 31 March 1920, and began working full-time for the party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The party headquarters was in Munich, a centre for anti-government German nationalists determined to eliminate Marxism and undermine the Weimar Republic.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In February 1921, already highly effective at crowd manipulation, Hitler spoke to a crowd of over 6,000.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] To publicise the meeting, two truckloads of party supporters drove around Munich waving swastika flags and distributing leaflets.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler soon gained notoriety for his rowdy polemic speeches against the Treaty of Versailles, rival politicians, and especially against Marxists and Jews.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In June 1921, while Hitler and Eckart were on a fundraising trip to Berlin, a mutiny broke out within the Nazi Party in Munich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Members of its executive committee wanted to merge with the Nuremberg-based German Socialist Party (DSP).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler returned to Munich on 11 July and angrily tendered his resignation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee members realised that the resignation of their leading public figure and speaker would mean the end of the party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler announced he would rejoin on the condition that he would replace Drexler as party chairman, and that the party headquarters would remain in Munich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee agreed, and he rejoined the party on 26 July as member 3,680.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler continued to face some opposition within the Nazi Party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Opponents of Hitler in the leadership had Hermann Esser expelled from the party, and they printed 3,000 copies of a pamphlet attacking Hitler as a traitor to the party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In the following days, Hitler spoke to several large audiences and defended himself and Esser, to thunderous applause.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His strategy proved successful, and at a special party congress on 29 July, he was granted absolute power as party chairman, succeeding Drexler, by a vote of 533 to 1.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's vitriolic beer hall speeches began attracting regular audiences.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] A demagogue, he became adept at using populist themes, including the use of scapegoats, who were blamed for his listeners' economic hardships.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used personal magnetism and an understanding of crowd psychology to his advantage while engaged in public speaking.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Historians have noted the hypnotic effect of his rhetoric on large audiences, and of his eyes in small groups.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Early followers included Rudolf Hess, the former air force ace Hermann Göring, and the army captain Ernst Röhm.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Röhm became head of the Nazis' paramilitary organisation, the *Sturmabteilung* (SA, "Stormtroopers"), which protected meetings and attacked political opponents.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] A critical influence on Hitler's thinking during this period was the *Aufbau Vereinigung*, a conspiratorial group of White Russian exiles and early Nazis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The group, financed with funds channelled from wealthy industrialists, introduced Hitler to the idea of a Jewish conspiracy, linking international finance with Bolshevism.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The programme of the Nazi Party was laid out in their 25-point programme on 24 February 1920.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] This did not represent a coherent ideology, but was a conglomeration of received ideas which had currency in the *völkisch* pan-Germanic movement, such as ultranationalism, opposition to the Treaty of Versailles, distrust of capitalism, as well as some socialist ideas.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] For Hitler, the most important aspect of it was its strong antisemitic stance.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He also perceived the programme as primarily a basis for propaganda and for attracting people to the party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, Hitler enlisted the help of World War I General Erich Ludendorff for an attempted coup known as the Beer Hall Putsch.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party used Italian Fascism as a model for their appearance and policies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler wanted to emulate Benito Mussolini's March on Rome in 1922 by staging his own coup in Bavaria, to be followed by a challenge to the government in Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and Ludendorff sought the support of *Staatskommissar* (State Commissioner) Gustav Ritter von Kahr, Bavaria's *de facto* ruler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] However, Kahr, along with Police Chief Hans Ritter von Seisser and Reichswehr General Otto von Lossow, wanted to install a nationalist dictatorship without Hitler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 8 November 1923, Hitler and the SA stormed a public meeting of 3,000 people organised by Kahr in the Bürgerbräukeller, a beer hall in Munich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Interrupting Kahr's speech, he announced that the national revolution had begun and declared the formation of a new government with Ludendorff.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Retiring to a back room, Hitler, with his pistol drawn, demanded and subsequently received the support of Kahr, Seisser, and Lossow.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's forces initially succeeded in occupying the local Reichswehr and police headquarters, but Kahr and his cohorts quickly withdrew their support.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Neither the Army nor the state police joined forces with Hitler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The next day, Hitler and his followers marched from the beer hall to the Bavarian War Ministry to overthrow the Bavarian government, but police dispersed them.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In the failed coup, 16 Nazi Party members and four police officers were killed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler fled to the home of Ernst Hanfstaengl and by some accounts contemplated suicide.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He was depressed but calm when arrested on 11 November 1923 for high treason.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] His trial before the special People's Court in Munich began in February 1924, and Alfred Rosenberg became the temporary leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 April, Hitler was sentenced to five years' *Festungshaft* ('fortress confinement') at Landsberg Prison.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] There, he received friendly treatment from the guards and was allowed mail from supporters and regular visits by party comrades.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Pardoned by the Bavarian Supreme Court, he was released from jail on 20 December 1924, against the state prosecutor's objections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Including time on remand, Hitler served just over one year in prison.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While at Landsberg, Hitler dictated most of the first volume of *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] 'My Struggle'; originally titled *Four and a Half Years of Struggle against Lies, Stupidity, and Cowardice*) at first to his chauffeur, Emil Maurice, and then to his deputy, Rudolf Hess.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The book, dedicated to Thule Society member Dietrich Eckart, was an autobiography and exposition of his ideology.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The book laid out Hitler's plans for territorial expansion as well as transforming German society into a dictatorship based on race.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Throughout the book, Jews are equated with "germs" and presented as the "international poisoners" of society.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] According to Hitler's ideology, the only solution was their extermination.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler did not describe exactly how this was to be accomplished, his "inherent genocidal thrust is undeniable", according to Ian Kershaw.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Published in two volumes in 1925 and 1926, *Mein Kampf* sold 228,000 copies between 1925 and 1932.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] One million copies were sold in 1933, Hitler's first year in office.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly before Hitler was eligible for parole, the Bavarian government attempted to have him deported to Austria.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Austrian federal chancellor rejected the request on the specious grounds that his service in the German Army made his Austrian citizenship void.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler formally renounced his Austrian citizenship on 7 April 1925.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At the time of Hitler's release from prison, politics in Germany had become less combative, and the economy had improved, limiting Hitler's opportunities for political agitation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] As a result of the failed Beer Hall Putsch, the Nazi Party and its affiliated organisations were banned in Bavaria.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with the prime minister of Bavaria, Heinrich Held, on 4 January 1925, Hitler agreed to respect the state's authority and promised that he would seek political power only through the democratic process.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The meeting paved the way for the ban on the Nazi Party to be lifted on 16 February.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] However, after an inflammatory speech he gave on 27 February, Hitler was barred from public speaking by the Bavarian authorities, a ban that remained in place until 1927.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] To advance his political ambitions despite the ban, Hitler appointed Gregor Strasser, Otto Strasser, and Joseph Goebbels to organise and enlarge the Nazi Party in northern Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Gregor Strasser steered a more independent political course, emphasising the socialist elements of the party's programme.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The stock market in the United States crashed on 24 October 1929.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The impact in Germany was dire: millions became unemployed, and several major banks collapsed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazi Party prepared to take advantage of the emergency to gain support for their party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] They promised to repudiate the Versailles Treaty, strengthen the economy, and provide jobs.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Great Depression provided a political opportunity for Hitler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Germans were ambivalent about the parliamentary republic, which faced challenges from right- and left-wing extremists.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The moderate political parties were increasingly unable to stem the tide of extremism, and the German referendum of 1929 helped to elevate Nazi ideology.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The elections of September 1930 resulted in the break-up of a grand coalition and its replacement with a minority cabinet.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Its leader, chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party, governed through emergency decrees from President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Governance by decree became the new norm, paving the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party rose from obscurity to win 18.3 per cent of the vote and 107 parliamentary seats in the 1930 election, becoming the second-largest party in parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made a prominent appearance at the trial of two Reichswehr officers, Lieutenants Richard Scheringer and Hanns Ludin, in late 1930.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Both were charged with membership in the Nazi Party, at that time illegal for Reichswehr personnel.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The prosecution argued that the Nazi Party was extremist, prompting defence lawyer Hans Frank to call on Hitler to testify.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 September 1930, Hitler testified that his party would pursue political power solely through democratic elections, which won him many supporters in the officer corps.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Brüning's austerity measures brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler exploited this by targeting his political messages specifically at people who had been affected by the inflation of the 1920s and the Depression, such as farmers, war veterans, and the middle class.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Although Hitler had terminated his Austrian citizenship in 1925, he did not acquire German citizenship for almost seven years.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] This meant that he was stateless, legally unable to run for public office, and still faced the risk of deportation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 February 1932, the interior minister of Brunswick, Dietrich Klagges, who was a member of the Nazi Party, appointed Hitler as administrator for the state's delegation to the Reichsrat in Berlin, making Hitler a citizen of Brunswick, and thus of Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler ran against Hindenburg in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] A speech to the Industry Club in Düsseldorf on 27 January 1932 won him support from many of Germany's most powerful industrialists.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg had support from various nationalist, monarchist, Catholic, and republican parties, and some Social Democrats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used the campaign slogan "*Hitler über Deutschland*" ("Hitler over Germany"), a reference to his political ambitions and his campaigning by aircraft.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He was one of the first politicians to use aircraft travel for campaigning and used it effectively.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler came in second in both rounds of the election, garnering more than 35 per cent of the vote in the final election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Although he lost to Hindenburg, this election established Hitler as a strong force in German politics.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The absence of an effective government prompted two influential politicians, Franz von Papen and Alfred Hugenberg, along with several other industrialists and businessmen, to write a letter to Hindenburg.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The signers urged Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as leader of a government "independent from parliamentary parties", which could turn into a movement that would "enrapture millions of people".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg reluctantly agreed to appoint Hitler as chancellor after two further parliamentary elections—in July and November 1932—had not resulted in the formation of a majority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler headed a short-lived coalition government formed by the Nazi Party (which had the most seats in the Reichstag) and Hugenberg's party, the German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 30 January 1933, the new cabinet was sworn in during a brief ceremony in Hindenburg's office.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party gained three posts: Hitler was named chancellor, Wilhelm Frick Minister of the Interior, and Hermann Göring Minister of the Interior for Prussia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler had insisted on the ministerial positions as a way to gain control over the police in much of Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] As chancellor, Hitler worked against attempts by the Nazi Party's opponents to build a majority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Because of the political stalemate, he asked Hindenburg to again dissolve the Reichstag, and elections were scheduled for early March.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 27 February 1933, the Reichstag building was set on fire.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Göring blamed a communist plot, as the Dutch communist Marinus van der Lubbe was found in incriminating circumstances inside the burning building.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Until the 1960s, some historians, including William L.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Shirer and Alan Bullock, thought the Nazi Party was responsible; now the view of most historians is van der Lubbe started the fire alone.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At Hitler's urging, Hindenburg responded by signing the Reichstag Fire Decree of 28 February, drafted by the Nazis, which suspended basic rights and allowed detention without trial.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The decree was permitted under Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution, which gave the president the power to take emergency measures to protect public safety and order.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Activities of the German Communist Party (KPD) were suppressed, and 4,000 KPD members were arrested.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition to political campaigning, the Nazi Party engaged in paramilitary violence and the spread of anti-communist propaganda, in the days preceding the election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On election day, 6 March 1933, the Nazis’ share of the vote increased to 44%, and the party acquired the largest number of seats in parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's party failed to secure an absolute majority, necessitating another coalition with the DNVP.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 March 1933, the new *Reichstag* was constituted with an opening ceremony at the Garrison Church in Potsdam.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] This "Day of Potsdam" was held to demonstrate unity between the Nazi movement and the old Prussian elite and military.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler appeared in a morning coat and humbly greeted Hindenburg.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] To achieve full political control despite not having an absolute majority in parliament, Hitler's government brought the *Ermächtigungsgesetz* (Enabling Act) to a vote in the newly elected *Reichstag*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act—officially titled the *Gesetz zur Behebung der Not von Volk und Reich* ("Law to Remedy the Distress of People and Reich")—gave Hitler's cabinet the power to enact laws without the consent of the Reichstag for four years.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] These laws could (with certain exceptions) deviate from the constitution.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Since it would affect the constitution, the Enabling Act required a two-thirds majority to pass.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Leaving nothing to chance, the Nazis used the provisions of the Reichstag Fire Decree to arrest all 81 Communist deputies (in spite of their virulent campaign against the party, the Nazis had allowed the KPD to contest the election) and prevent several Social Democrats from attending.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 23 March 1933, the *Reichstag* assembled at the Kroll Opera House under turbulent circumstances.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Ranks of SA men served as guards inside the building, while large groups outside, opposing the proposed legislation, shouted slogans and threats towards the arriving members of parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] After Hitler verbally promised Centre party leader Ludwig Kaas that Hindenburg would retain his power of veto, Kaas announced the Centre Party would support the Enabling Act.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act was passed by a vote of 444–94, with all parties except the Social Democrats voting in favour.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Enabling Act, along with the Reichstag Fire Decree, transformed Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Having achieved full control over the legislative and executive branches of government, Hitler and his allies began to suppress the remaining opposition.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Social Democratic Party was made illegal, and its assets were seized.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While many trade union delegates were in Berlin for May Day activities, SA stormtroopers occupied union offices around the country.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 2 May 1933, all trade unions were forced to dissolve, and their leaders were arrested.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The German Labour Front was formed as an umbrella organisation to represent all workers, administrators, and company owners, thus reflecting the concept of Nazism in the spirit of Hitler's *Volksgemeinschaft* ("people's community").
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of June, the other parties had been intimidated into disbanding.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] This included the Nazis' nominal coalition partner, the DNVP; with the SA's help, Hitler forced its leader, Hugenberg, to resign on 29 June.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 14 July 1933, the Nazi Party was declared the only legal political party in Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The demands of the SA for more political and military power caused anxiety among military, industrial, and political leaders.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler purged the entire SA leadership in the Night of the Long Knives, which took place from 30 June to 2 July 1934.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler targeted Ernst Röhm and other SA leaders who, along with several Hitler's political adversaries (such as Gregor Strasser and former chancellor Kurt von Schleicher), were rounded up, arrested, and shot.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While the international community and some Germans were shocked by the killings, many in Germany believed Hitler was restoring order.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On the previous day, the cabinet had enacted the Law Concerning the Head of State of the German Reich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] This law stated that upon Hindenburg's death, the office of president would be abolished, and its powers merged with those of the chancellor.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler thus became head of state as well as head of government and was formally named as *Führer und Reichskanzler* (Leader and Chancellor of the Reich), although *Reichskanzler* was eventually dropped.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] With this action, Hitler eliminated the last legal remedy by which he could be removed from office.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] As head of state, Hitler became commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 19 August, the merger of the presidency with the chancellorship was approved by 88 per cent of the electorate voting in a plebiscite.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, Hitler used blackmail to consolidate his hold over the military by instigating the Blomberg–Fritsch affair.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler forced his War Minister, Field Marshal Werner von Blomberg, to resign by using a police dossier that showed that Blomberg's new wife had a record for prostitution.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Army commander Colonel-General Werner von Fritsch was removed after the *Schutzstaffel* (SS) produced allegations that he had engaged in a homosexual relationship.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Both men had fallen into disfavour because they objected to Hitler's demand to make the *Wehrmacht* ready for war as early as 1938.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler assumed Blomberg's title of Commander-in-Chief, thus taking personal command of the armed forces.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He replaced the Ministry of War with the *Oberkommando der Wehrmacht* (OKW), headed by General Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On the same day, 16 generals were stripped of their commands, and 44 more were transferred; all were suspected of not being sufficiently pro-Nazi.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] By early February 1938, 12 more generals had been removed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler took care to give his dictatorship the appearance of legality.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of his decrees were explicitly based on the Reichstag Fire Decree and hence on Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The *Reichstag* renewed the Enabling Act twice, each time for four years.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] While elections to the *Reichstag* were still held (in 1933, 1936, and 1938), voters were presented with a single list of Nazis and pro-Nazi "guests" which received well over 90 per cent of the vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] These sham elections were held in far-from-secret conditions; the Nazis threatened severe reprisals against anyone who did not vote or who voted against.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1934, Hitler appointed *Reichsbank* President Hjalmar Schacht as Minister of Economics, and in the following year, as Plenipotentiary for War Economy in charge of preparing the economy for war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Reconstruction and rearmament were financed through Mefo bills, printing money, and seizing the assets of people arrested as enemies of the state, including Jews.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of unemployed fell from six million in 1932 to fewer than one million in 1936.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler oversaw one of the largest infrastructure improvement campaigns in German history, leading to the construction of dams, *autobahns*, railroads, and other civil works.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Wages were slightly lower in the mid- to late 1930s compared with wages during the Weimar Republic, while the cost of living increased by 25 per cent.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The average workweek increased during the shift to a war economy; by 1939, the average German was working between 47 and 50 hours a week.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's government sponsored architecture on an immense scale.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Albert Speer, instrumental in implementing Hitler's classicist reinterpretation of German culture, was placed in charge of the proposed architectural renovations of Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Despite a threatened multi-nation boycott, Germany hosted the 1936 Olympic Games.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler officiated at the opening ceremonies and attended events at both the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen and the Summer Games in Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with German military leaders on 3 February 1933, Hitler spoke of "conquest for *Lebensraum* in the East and its ruthless Germanisation" as his ultimate foreign policy objectives.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler found Bülow's goals to be too modest.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In speeches during this period, he stressed what he termed the peaceful goals of his policies and a willingness to work within international agreements.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At the first meeting of his cabinet in 1933, Hitler prioritised military spending over unemployment relief.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany withdrew from the League of Nations and the World Disarmament Conference in October 1933.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In January 1935, over 90 per cent of the people of the Saarland, then under League of Nations administration, voted to unite with Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] That March, Hitler announced an expansion of the Wehrmacht to 600,000 members—six times the number permitted by the Versailles Treaty—including development of an air force (*Luftwaffe*) and an increase in the size of the navy (*Kriegsmarine*).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, France, Italy, and the League of Nations condemned these violations of the Treaty but did nothing to stop them.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The Anglo-German Naval Agreement (AGNA) of 18 June allowed German tonnage to increase to 35 per cent of that of the Royal Navy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler called the signing of the AGNA "the happiest day of his life", believing that the agreement marked the beginning of the Anglo-German alliance he had predicted in *Mein Kampf*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] France and Italy were not consulted before the signing, directly undermining the League of Nations and setting the Treaty of Versailles on the path towards irrelevance.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany reoccupied the demilitarised zone in the Rhineland in March 1936, in violation of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sent troops to Spain to support Francisco Franco and his Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War after receiving an appeal for help in July 1936.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At the same time, Hitler continued his efforts to create an Anglo-German alliance.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1936, in response to a growing economic crisis caused by his rearmament efforts, Hitler ordered Göring to implement a Four Year Plan to prepare Germany for war within the next four years.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] The plan envisaged an all-out struggle between "Judaeo-Bolshevism" and German Nazism, which in Hitler's view required a committed effort of rearmament regardless of the economic costs.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In October 1936, Count Galeazzo Ciano, foreign minister of Mussolini's government, visited Germany, where he signed a Nine-Point Protocol as an expression of *rapprochement* and had a personal meeting with Hitler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 November, Mussolini declared an "axis" between Germany and Italy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 November, Germany signed the Anti-Comintern Pact with Japan.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, China, Italy, and Poland were also invited to join the Anti-Comintern Pact, but only Italy signed in 1937.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler abandoned his plan of an Anglo-German alliance, blaming "inadequate" British leadership.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] At a meeting in the Reich Chancellery with his foreign ministers and military chiefs that November, Hitler restated his intention of acquiring *Lebensraum* for the German people.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He ordered preparations for war in the East to begin as early as 1938 and no later than 1943.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In the event of his death, the conference minutes, recorded as the Hossbach Memorandum, were to be regarded as his "political testament".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] He felt that a severe decline in living standards in Germany as a result of the economic crisis could only be stopped by military aggression aimed at seizing Austria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler urged quick action before Britain and France gained a permanent lead in the arms race.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, in the wake of the Blomberg–Fritsch affair, Hitler asserted control of the military-foreign policy apparatus, dismissing Neurath as foreign minister and appointing himself as War Minister.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p01] From early 1938 onwards, Hitler was carrying out a foreign policy ultimately aimed at war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In February 1938, on the advice of his newly appointed foreign minister, the strongly pro-Japanese Joachim von Ribbentrop, Hitler ended the Sino-German alliance with the Republic of China to instead enter into an alliance with the more modern and powerful Empire of Japan.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler announced German recognition of Manchukuo, the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria, and renounced German claims to their former colonies in the Pacific held by Japan.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered an end to arms shipments to China and recalled all German officers working with the Chinese Army.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In retaliation, Chinese General Chiang Kai-shek cancelled all Sino-German economic agreements, depriving the Germans of many Chinese raw materials.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 March 1938, Hitler announced the unification of Austria with Germany in the *Anschluss*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler then turned his attention to the ethnic German population of the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28–29 March 1938, Hitler held a series of secret meetings in Berlin with Konrad Henlein of the Sudeten German Party, the largest of the ethnic German parties of the Sudetenland.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The men agreed that Henlein would demand increased autonomy for Sudeten Germans from the Czechoslovak government, thus providing a pretext for German military action against Czechoslovakia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In April 1938, Henlein told the foreign minister of Hungary that "whatever the Czech government might offer, he would always raise still higher demands ... he wanted to sabotage an understanding by any means because this was the only method to blow up Czechoslovakia quickly".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In private, Hitler considered the Sudeten issue unimportant; his real intention was a war of conquest against Czechoslovakia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler ordered the OKW to prepare for *Fall Grün* (Case Green), the code name for an invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of intense French and British diplomatic pressure, on 5 September, Czechoslovak president Edvard Beneš unveiled the "Fourth Plan" for constitutional reorganisation of his country, which agreed to most of Henlein's demands for Sudeten autonomy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Henlein's party responded to Beneš's offer by instigating a series of violent clashes with the Czechoslovak police that led to the declaration of martial law in certain Sudeten districts.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany was dependent on imported oil; a confrontation with Britain over the Czechoslovak dispute could curtail Germany's oil supplies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] This forced Hitler to call off *Fall Grün*, originally planned for 1 October 1938.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 29 September, Hitler, Neville Chamberlain, Édouard Daladier, and Mussolini attended a one-day conference in Munich that led to the Munich Agreement, which handed over the Sudetenland districts to Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Chamberlain was satisfied with the Munich conference, calling the outcome "peace for our time", while Hitler was angered about the missed opportunity for war in 1938; he expressed his disappointment in a speech on 9 October in Saarbrücken.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In Hitler's view, the British-brokered peace, although favourable to the ostensible German demands, was a diplomatic defeat which spurred his intent of limiting British power to pave the way for the eastern expansion of Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of the summit, Hitler was selected *Time* magazine's Man of the Year for 1938.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1938 and early 1939, the continuing economic crisis caused by rearmament forced Hitler to make major defence cuts.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In his "Export or die" speech of 30 January 1939, he called for an economic offensive to increase German foreign exchange holdings to pay for raw materials such as high-grade iron needed for military weapons.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 14 March 1939, under threat from Hungary, Slovakia declared independence and received protection from Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The next day, in violation of the Munich Agreement and possibly as a result of the deepening economic crisis requiring additional assets, Hitler ordered the Wehrmacht to invade the Czech rump state, and from Prague Castle he proclaimed the territory a German protectorate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In private discussions in 1939, Hitler declared Britain the main enemy to be defeated and that Poland's obliteration was a necessary prelude for that goal.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The eastern flank would be secured, and land would be added to Germany's *Lebensraum*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Offended by the British "guarantee" on 31 March 1939 of Polish independence, he said, "I shall brew them a devil's drink".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In a speech in Wilhelmshaven for the launch of the battleship *Tirpitz* on 1 April, he threatened to denounce the Anglo-German Naval Agreement if the British continued to guarantee Polish independence, which he perceived as an "encirclement" policy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Poland was to either become a German satellite state, or it would be neutralised to secure the Reich's eastern flank and prevent a possible British blockade.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler initially favoured the idea of a satellite state, but upon its rejection by the Polish government, he decided to invade and made this the main foreign policy goal of 1939.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 3 April, Hitler ordered the military to prepare for *Fall Weiss* ("Case White"), the plan for invading Poland on 25 August.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In a Reichstag speech on 28 April, he renounced both the Anglo-German Naval Agreement and the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians such as William Carr, Gerhard Weinberg, and Ian Kershaw have argued that one reason for Hitler's rush to war was his fear of an early death.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He had repeatedly claimed that he must lead Germany into war before he got too old, as his successors might lack his strength of will.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was concerned that a military attack against Poland could result in a premature war with Britain.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's foreign minister and former Ambassador to London, Joachim von Ribbentrop, assured him that neither Britain nor France would honour its commitments to Poland.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Accordingly, on 22 August 1939, Hitler ordered a military mobilisation against Poland.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] This plan required tacit Soviet support, and the non-aggression pact (the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact) between Germany and the Soviet Union, led by Joseph Stalin, included a secret agreement to partition Poland between the two countries.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Contrary to Ribbentrop's prediction that Britain would sever Anglo-Polish ties, Britain and Poland signed the Anglo-Polish alliance on 25 August 1939.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] This, along with news from Italy that Mussolini would not honour the Pact of Steel, prompted Hitler to postpone the attack on Poland from 25 August to 1 September.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler unsuccessfully tried to manoeuvre the British into neutrality by offering them a non-aggression guarantee on 25 August; he then instructed Ribbentrop to present a last-minute peace plan with an impossibly short time limit in an effort to blame the imminent war on British and Polish inaction.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded western Poland under the pretext of having been denied claims to the Free City of Danzig and the right to extraterritorial roads across the Polish Corridor, which Germany had ceded under the Versailles Treaty.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In response, Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September, surprising Hitler and prompting him to angrily ask Ribbentrop, "Now what?" Britain and France did not act on their declarations immediately, and on 17 September, Soviet forces invaded eastern Poland.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The fall of Poland was followed by what contemporary journalists dubbed the "Phoney War" or *Sitzkrieg* ("sitting war").
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler instructed the two newly appointed Gauleiters of north-western Poland, Albert Forster of Reichsgau Danzig-West Prussia and Arthur Greiser of Reichsgau Wartheland, to Germanise their areas, with "no questions asked" about how this was accomplished.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In Forster's area, ethnic Poles merely had to sign forms stating that they had German blood.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In contrast, Greiser agreed with Himmler and carried out an ethnic cleansing campaign towards Poles.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Greiser soon complained that Forster was allowing thousands of Poles to be accepted as "racial" Germans and thus endangered German "racial purity".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] This inaction has been cited as an example of the theory of "working towards the Führer", in which Hitler issued vague instructions and expected his subordinates to develop policies independently.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Another dispute pitched one side represented by Heinrich Himmler and Greiser, who championed ethnic cleansing in Poland, against another represented by Göring and Hans Frank (governor-general of occupied Poland), who called for turning Poland into the "granary" of the Reich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 February 1940, the dispute was initially settled in favour of the Göring–Frank view, which ended the economically disruptive mass expulsions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 May 1940, Himmler issued a memo entitled "Some Thoughts on the Treatment of Alien Population in the East", calling for the expulsion of the entire Jewish population of Europe into Africa and the reduction of the Polish population to a "leaderless class of labourers".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler called Himmler's memo "good and correct", and, ignoring Göring and Frank, implemented the Himmler–Greiser policy in Poland.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 9 April, German forces invaded Denmark and Norway.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On the same day, Hitler proclaimed the birth of the Greater Germanic Reich, his vision of a united empire of Germanic nations of Europe in which the Dutch, Flemish, and Scandinavians were joined into a "racially pure" polity under German leadership.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In May 1940, Germany attacked France, and conquered Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] These victories prompted Mussolini to have Italy join forces with Hitler on 10 June.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] France and Germany signed an armistice on 22 June.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw notes that Hitler's popularity within Germany—and German support for the war—reached its peak when he returned to Berlin on 6 July from his tour of Paris.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the unexpected swift victory, Hitler promoted 12 generals to the rank of field marshal during the 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Britain, whose troops were forced to evacuate France by sea from Dunkirk, continued to fight alongside other British dominions in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler made peace overtures to the new British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and upon their rejection, he ordered a series of aerial attacks on Royal Air Force airbases and radar stations in southeast England.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 September, the systematic nightly bombing of London began.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The German Luftwaffe failed to defeat the Royal Air Force in what became known as the Battle of Britain.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By the end of September, Hitler realised that air superiority for the invasion of Britain (in Operation Sea Lion) could not be achieved, and ordered the operation postponed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The nightly air raids on British cities intensified and continued for months, including London, Plymouth, and Coventry.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 27 September 1940, the Tripartite Pact was signed in Berlin by Saburō Kurusu of Imperial Japan, Hitler, and Italian foreign minister Ciano, and later expanded to include Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria, thus yielding the Axis powers.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's attempt to integrate the Soviet Union into the anti-British bloc failed after inconclusive talks between Hitler and Molotov in Berlin in November, and he ordered preparations for the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In early 1941, German forces were deployed to North Africa, the Balkans, and the Middle East.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In February, German forces arrived in Libya to bolster the Italian presence.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler launched the invasion of Yugoslavia, quickly followed by the invasion of Greece.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In May, German forces were sent to support Iraqi forces fighting against the British and to invade Crete.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 November, Hitler met in Berlin with Amin al-Husseini, the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 June 1941, contravening the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, over three million Axis troops attacked the Soviet Union.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] This offensive (codenamed Operation Barbarossa) was intended to destroy the Soviet Union and seize its natural resources for subsequent aggression against the Western powers.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The action was also part of the overall plan to obtain more living space for German people; and Hitler thought a successful invasion would force Britain to negotiate a surrender.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The invasion conquered a huge area, including the Baltic republics, Belarus, and West Ukraine.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By early August, Axis troops had advanced 500 km (310 miles) and won the Battle of Smolensk.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Army Group Centre to temporarily halt its advance to Moscow and divert its Panzer groups to aid in the encirclement of Leningrad and Kiev.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] His generals disagreed with this change, having advanced within 400 km (250 miles) of Moscow, and his decision caused a crisis among the military leadership.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The pause provided the Red Army with an opportunity to mobilise fresh reserves; the historian Russel Stolfi considers it to be one of the major factors that caused the failure of the Moscow offensive, which was resumed in October 1941 and ended disastrously in December.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] During this crisis, Hitler appointed himself as head of the *Oberkommando des Heeres*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 December 1941, Japan attacked the American fleet based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Four days later, Hitler declared war against the United States.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 18 December 1941, Himmler asked Hitler, "What to do with the Jews of Russia?", to which Hitler replied, *"als Partisanen auszurotten"* ("exterminate them as partisans").
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The Israeli historian Yehuda Bauer has commented that the remark is probably as close as historians will ever get to a definitive order from Hitler for the genocide carried out during the Holocaust.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1942, German forces were defeated in the Second Battle of El Alamein, thwarting Hitler's plans to seize the Suez Canal and the Middle East.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Overconfident in his own military expertise following the earlier victories in 1940, Hitler became distrustful of his Army High Command and began to interfere in military and tactical planning, with damaging consequences.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In December 1942 and January 1943, Hitler's repeated refusal to allow their withdrawal at the Battle of Stalingrad led to the near-destruction of the 6th Army.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Over 200,000 Axis soldiers were killed, and 235,000 were taken prisoner.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Thereafter came a decisive strategic defeat at the Battle of Kursk.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's military judgment became increasingly erratic, and Germany's military and economic position deteriorated, as did Hitler's health.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily in 1943, Mussolini was removed from power by King Victor Emmanuel III after a vote of no confidence of the Grand Council of Fascism.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Marshal Pietro Badoglio, placed in charge of the government, soon surrendered to the Allies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Throughout 1943 and 1944, the Soviet Union steadily forced Hitler's armies into retreat along the Eastern Front.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 6 June 1944, the Western Allied armies landed in northern France in one of the largest amphibious operations in history, Operation Overlord.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Many German officers concluded that defeat was inevitable and that continuing under Hitler's leadership would result in the complete destruction of the country.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Between 1939 and 1945, there were numerous plans to assassinate Hitler, some of which proceeded to significant degrees.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The most well-known and significant, the 20 July plot of 1944, came from within Germany and was at least partly driven by the increasing prospect of a German defeat in the war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Part of Operation Valkyrie, the plot involved Claus von Stauffenberg planting a bomb in one of Hitler's headquarters, the Wolf's Lair at Rastenburg.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler narrowly survived because the staff officer Heinz Brandt moved the briefcase containing the bomb behind a leg of the heavy conference table, which deflected much of the blast.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Later, Hitler ordered reprisals, resulting in the execution of more than 4,900 people.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was put on the United Nations War Crimes Commission's first list of war criminals in December 1944, after determining that Hitler could be held criminally responsible for the acts of the Nazis in occupied countries.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By March 1945, at least seven indictments had been filed against him.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By late 1944, both the Red Army and the Western Allies were advancing into Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Recognising the strength and determination of the Red Army, Hitler decided to use his remaining mobile reserves against the American and British armies, which he perceived as far weaker.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 16 December, he launched the Ardennes Offensive to incite disunity among the Western Allies and perhaps convince them to join his fight against the Soviets.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] After some temporary successes, the offensive failed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In any case only those who are inferior will remain after this struggle, for the good have already been killed".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The same day, Hitler ordered the destruction of all German industrial infrastructure before it could fall into Allied hands.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Minister for Armaments Albert Speer was entrusted with executing this scorched earth policy, but he secretly disobeyed the order.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's hope to negotiate peace with the United States and Britain was encouraged by the death of US president Franklin D.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Roosevelt on 12 April 1945, but contrary to his expectations, this caused no rift among the Allies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 20 April, his 56th birthday, Hitler made his last trip from the *Führerbunker* to the surface.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In the ruined garden of the Reich Chancellery, he awarded Iron Crosses to boy soldiers of the Hitler Youth, who were now fighting the Red Army at the front near Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By 21 April, Georgy Zhukov's 1st Belorussian Front had broken through the defences of General Gotthard Heinrici's Army Group Vistula during the Battle of the Seelow Heights and advanced to the outskirts of Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In denial about the dire situation, Hitler placed his hopes on the undermanned and under-equipped *Armeeabteilung Steiner* (Army Detachment Steiner), commanded by Felix Steiner.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Steiner to attack the northern flank of the salient, while the German Ninth Army was ordered to attack northward in a pincer attack.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] During a military conference on 22 April, Hitler enquired about Steiner's offensive.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He was informed that the attack had not been launched and that the Soviets had entered Berlin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered everyone but Wilhelm Keitel, Alfred Jodl, Hans Krebs, and Wilhelm Burgdorf to leave the room, then launched into a tirade against the perceived treachery and incompetence of his generals, culminating in his declaration—for the first time—that "everything is lost".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He announced that he would stay in Berlin until the end and then shoot himself.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By 23 April, the Red Army had surrounded Berlin, and Goebbels made a proclamation urging its citizens to defend the city.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] That same day, Göring sent a telegram from Berchtesgaden, arguing that as Hitler was isolated in Berlin, Göring should assume leadership of Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Göring set a deadline, after which he would consider Hitler incapacitated.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler responded by having Göring arrested, and in his last will and testament of 29 April, he removed Göring from all government positions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 April, Hitler discovered that Himmler, who had left Berlin on 20 April, was attempting to negotiate a surrender to the Western Allies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He considered this treason and ordered Himmler's arrest.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He also ordered the execution of Hermann Fegelein, Himmler's SS representative at Hitler's headquarters in Berlin, for desertion.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] After midnight on the night of 28–29 April, Hitler married Eva Braun in a small civil ceremony in the *Führerbunker*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Later that afternoon, Hitler was informed that Mussolini had been executed by the Italian resistance movement on the previous day; this is believed to have increased his determination to avoid capture.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 30 April, Soviet troops were within five hundred metres of the Reich Chancellery when Hitler shot himself in the head and Braun bit into a cyanide capsule.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In accordance with Hitler's wishes, their corpses were carried outside to the garden behind the Reich Chancellery, where they were placed in a bomb crater, doused with petrol, and set on fire as the Red Army shelling continued.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz and Goebbels assumed Hitler's roles as head of state and chancellor respectively.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On the evening of 1 May, Goebbels and his wife, Magda, committed suicide in the Reich Chancellery garden, after having poisoned their six children with cyanide.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The remains of the Goebbels family, General Hans Krebs (who had committed suicide that day), and Hitler's dog Blondi were repeatedly buried and exhumed by the Soviets.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's and Braun's remains were alleged to have been moved as well, but this is most likely Soviet disinformation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] There is no evidence that any identifiable remains of Hitler or Braun—with the exception of dental bridges—were ever found by them.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] While news of Hitler's death spread quickly, a death certificate was not issued until 1956, after a lengthy investigation to collect testimony from 42 witnesses.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's death was entered as an assumption of death based on this testimony.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The Holocaust and Germany's war in the East were based on Hitler's long-standing view that the Jews were the enemy of the German people, and that *Lebensraum* was needed for Germany's expansion.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He focused on Eastern Europe for this expansion, aiming to defeat Poland and the Soviet Union and then removing or killing the Jews and Slavs.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The *Generalplan Ost* (General Plan East) called for deporting the population of occupied Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to West Siberia, for use as slave labour or to be murdered; the conquered territories were to be colonised by German or "Germanised" settlers.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The goal was to implement this plan after the conquest of the Soviet Union, but when this failed, Hitler moved the plans forward.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By January 1942, he had decided that the Jews, Slavs, and other deportees considered undesirable should be killed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The genocide was organised and executed by Heinrich Himmler and Reinhard Heydrich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The records of the Wannsee Conference, held on 20 January 1942 and led by Heydrich, with 15 senior Nazi officials participating, provide the clearest evidence of systematic planning for the Holocaust.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 February, Hitler was recorded saying, "we shall regain our health only by eliminating the Jews".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Similarly, at a meeting in July 1941 with leading functionaries of the Eastern territories, Hitler said that the easiest way to quickly pacify the areas would be best achieved by "shooting everyone who even looks odd".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Although no direct order from Hitler authorising the mass killings has surfaced, his public speeches, orders to his generals, and the diaries of Nazi officials demonstrate that he conceived and authorised the extermination of European Jewry.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] During the war, Hitler repeatedly stated his prophecy of 1939 was being fulfilled, namely, that a world war would bring about the annihilation of the Jewish race.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler approved the *Einsatzgruppen*—killing squads that followed the German army through Poland, the Baltic, and the Soviet Union—and was well informed about their activities.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] By summer 1942, Auschwitz concentration camp was expanded to accommodate large numbers of deportees for murder or enslavement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Scores of other concentration camps and satellite camps were set up throughout Europe, with several camps devoted exclusively to extermination.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The victims were killed in concentration and extermination camps and in ghettos, and through mass shootings.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Many victims of the Holocaust were murdered in gas chambers or shot, while others died of starvation or disease or while working as slave labourers.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition to eliminating Jews, the Nazis planned to reduce the population of the conquered territories by 30 million people through starvation in an action called the Hunger Plan.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Food supplies would be diverted to the German army and German civilians.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Cities would be razed, and the land allowed to return to forest or resettled by German colonists.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Together, the Hunger Plan and *Generalplan Ost* would have led to the starvation of 80 million people in the Soviet Union.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] These partially fulfilled plans resulted in additional deaths, bringing the total number of civilians and prisoners of war who died in the democide to an estimated 19.3 million people.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies resulted in the killing of nearly two million non-Jewish Polish civilians, over three million Soviet prisoners of war, communists and other political opponents, homosexuals, the physically and mentally disabled, Jehovah's Witnesses, Adventists, and trade unionists.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler never spoke publicly about the killings and seems to have never visited the concentration camps.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The Nazis embraced the concept of racial hygiene.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 September 1935, Hitler presented two laws—known as the Nuremberg Laws—to the Reichstag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws banned sexual relations and marriages between Aryans and Jews and were later extended to include "Gypsies, Negroes or their bastard offspring".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws stripped all non-Aryans of their German citizenship and forbade the employment of non-Jewish women under the age of 45 in Jewish households.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's early eugenic policies targeted children with physical and developmental disabilities in a programme dubbed Action Brandt, and he later authorised a euthanasia programme for adults with serious mental and physical disabilities, now referred to as *Aktion T4*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ruled the Nazi Party autocratically by asserting the *Führerprinzip* (leader principle).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The principle relied on absolute obedience of all subordinates to their superiors; thus, he viewed the government structure as a pyramid, with himself—the infallible leader—at the apex.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Rank in the party was not determined by elections—positions were filled through appointment by those of higher rank, who demanded unquestioning obedience to the will of the leader.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership style was to give contradictory orders to his subordinates and to place them into positions where their duties and responsibilities overlapped with those of others, to have "the stronger one [do] the job".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In this way, Hitler fostered distrust, competition, and infighting among his subordinates to consolidate and maximise his own power.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] His cabinet never met after 1938, and he discouraged his ministers from meeting independently.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler typically did not give written orders; instead, he communicated verbally, or had them conveyed through his close associate Martin Bormann.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He entrusted Bormann with his paperwork, appointments, and personal finances; Bormann used his position to control the flow of information and access to Hitler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler dominated his country's war effort during World War II to a greater extent than any other national leader.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He strengthened his control of the armed forces in 1938, and subsequently made all major decisions regarding Germany's military strategy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] His decision to mount a risky series of offensives against Norway, France, and the Low Countries in 1940, against the advice of the military, proved successful, though the diplomatic and military strategies he employed in attempts to force the United Kingdom out of the war ended in failure.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler deepened his involvement in the war effort by appointing himself commander-in-chief of the Army in December 1941; from this point forward, he personally directed the war against the Soviet Union, while his military commanders facing the Western Allies retained a degree of autonomy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision-making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Nevertheless, he continued to believe that only his leadership could deliver victory.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In the final months of the war, Hitler refused to consider peace negotiations, regarding the destruction of Germany as preferable to surrender.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The military did not challenge Hitler's dominance of the war effort, and senior officers generally supported and enacted his decisions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler created a public image as a celibate man without a domestic life, dedicated entirely to his political mission and the nation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He met his lover, Eva Braun, in 1929, and married her on 29 April 1945, one day before they both committed suicide.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In September 1931, his half-niece, Geli Raubal, committed suicide with Hitler's gun in his Munich apartment.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] It was rumoured among contemporaries that Geli was in a romantic relationship with him, and her death was a source of deep, lasting pain.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Paula Hitler, the younger sister of Hitler and the last living member of his immediate family, died in June 1960.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was born to a practising Catholic mother and an anti-clerical father; after leaving home, Hitler never again attended Mass or received the sacraments.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Albert Speer stated that Hitler railed against the church to his political associates, and though he never officially left the church, he had no attachment to it.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer added that Hitler felt that in the absence of organised religion, people would turn to mysticism, which he considered regressive.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Speer, Hitler believed that Japanese religious beliefs or Islam would have been a more suitable religion for Germans than Christianity, with its "meekness and flabbiness".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Conway states that Hitler was fundamentally opposed to the Christian churches.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler did not believe in God, was anticlerical, and held Christian ethics in contempt because they contravened his preferred view of "survival of the fittest".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He favoured aspects of Protestantism that suited his own views, and adopted some elements of the Catholic Church's hierarchical organisation, liturgy, and phraseology.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In a 1932 speech, Hitler stated that he was not a Catholic, and declared himself a German Christian.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler viewed the church as an important politically conservative influence on society, and he adopted a strategic relationship with it that "suited his immediate political purposes".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In public, Hitler often praised Christian heritage and German Christian culture, though professing a belief in an "Aryan Jesus" who fought against the Jews.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] However, in *Hitler’s Table Talk* he was recorded as saying Christianity was an "absurdity" and nonsense founded on lies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] According to a US Office of Strategic Services (OSS) report, "The Nazi Master Plan", Hitler planned to destroy the influence of Christian churches within the Reich.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Shirer commented that "the Nazi regime intended to destroy Christianity in Germany, if it could, and substitute the old paganism of the early tribal Germanic gods with the new paganism of the Nazi extremists".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler wanted to wait until after the war before executing this plan.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Richard Steigmann-Gall has concluded there was no firm evidence of such a plan to replace Christianity.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Swedish historian Mikael Nilsson notes that many of Hitler's religious statements are sourced from *Table Talk*, which he considers highly unreliable: much of the content was written days after the event and was heavily modified to suit the agendas of Martin Bormann and later François Genoud.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer wrote that Hitler had a negative view of Himmler's and Alfred Rosenberg's mystical notions and Himmler's attempt to mythologise the SS.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was more pragmatic, and his ambitions centred on more practical concerns.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Researchers have variously suggested that Hitler suffered from irritable bowel syndrome, skin lesions, irregular heartbeat, coronary sclerosis, Parkinson's disease, syphilis, giant-cell arteritis, tinnitus, and monorchism.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In a report prepared for the OSS in 1943, Walter Charles Langer of Harvard University described Hitler as a "neurotic psychopath" and speculated that he exhibited masochistic tendencies and deep feelings of self-loathing, which he projected onto others, particularly Jews.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In his 1977 book *The Psychopathic God: Adolf Hitler*, the historian Robert G.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Waite proposes that Hitler suffered from borderline personality disorder.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The historians Henrik Eberle and Hans-Joachim Neumann consider that while he suffered from several illnesses, including Parkinson's disease, Hitler did not experience pathological delusions and was always fully aware of, and therefore responsible for, his decisions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Sometime in the 1930s, Hitler adopted a mainly vegetarian diet, avoiding all meat and fish from 1942 onwards.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] At social events, he sometimes gave graphic accounts of the slaughter of animals in an effort to make his guests shun meat.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Bormann had a greenhouse constructed near the Berghof (near Berchtesgaden) to ensure a steady supply of fresh fruit and vegetables for Hitler.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler stopped drinking alcohol around the time he became vegetarian and thereafter only very occasionally drank beer or wine on social occasions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He was a non-smoker for most of his adult life, but smoked heavily in his youth (25 to 40 cigarettes a day); he eventually quit, calling the habit "a waste of money".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He encouraged his close associates to quit by offering a gold watch to anyone able to break the habit.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler began using amphetamine occasionally after 1937 and became addicted to it in late 1942.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer linked this use of amphetamine to Hitler's increasingly erratic behaviour and inflexible decision-making (for example, rarely allowing military retreats).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Prescribed 90 medications during the war years by his personal physician, Theodor Morell, Hitler took many pills each day for chronic stomach problems and other ailments.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He regularly consumed amphetamine, barbiturates, opiates, and cocaine, as well as potassium bromide and atropa belladonna (the latter in the form of Doktor Koster's Antigaspills).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He suffered ruptured eardrums as a result of the 20 July plot bomb blast in 1944, and 200 wood splinters had to be removed from his legs.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Newsreel footage of Hitler shows tremors in his left hand and a shuffling walk, which began before the war and worsened towards the end of his life.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Ernst-Günther Schenck and several other doctors who met Hitler in the last weeks of his life also formed a diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian Joachim Fest, Hitler's suicide was likened by numerous contemporaries to a "spell" being broken.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian John Toland, Nazism "burst like a bubble" without its leader.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw describes Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] "Never in history has such ruination—physical and moral—been associated with the name of one man", he adds.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's political programme brought about a world war, leaving behind a devastated and impoverished Eastern and Central Europe.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany suffered wholesale destruction, characterised as *Stunde Null* (Zero Hour).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies inflicted human suffering on an unprecedented scale; according to R.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Rummel, the Nazi regime was responsible for the democidal killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The number of civilians killed during the Second World War was unprecedented in the history of warfare.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians, philosophers, and politicians often use the word "evil" to describe the Nazi regime.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Many European countries have criminalised both the promotion of Nazism and Holocaust denial.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Friedrich Meinecke described Hitler as "one of the great examples of the singular and incalculable power of personality in historical life".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The English historian Hugh Trevor-Roper saw him as "among the 'terrible simplifiers' of history, the most systematic, the most historical, the most philosophical, and yet the coarsest, cruelest, least magnanimous conqueror the world has ever known".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Roberts, Hitler's defeat marked the end of a phase of European history dominated by Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] In its place emerged the Cold War, a global confrontation between the Western Bloc, dominated by the United States and other NATO nations, and the Eastern Bloc, dominated by the Soviet Union.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Sebastian Haffner asserted that without Hitler and the displacement of the Jews, the modern nation-state of Israel would not exist.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He contends that without Hitler, the de-colonisation of former European spheres of influence would have been postponed.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Further, Haffner claimed that other than Alexander the Great, Hitler had a more significant impact than any other comparable historical figure, in that he too caused a wide range of worldwide changes in a relatively short time span.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler exploited documentary films and newsreels to inspire a cult of personality.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/adolf-hitler-p02] He was involved and appeared in a series of propaganda films throughout his political career, many made by Leni Riefenstahl, regarded as a pioneer of modern filmmaking.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland was born in 1941 in Chemnitz, a city that became part of East Germany in 1949 and was renamed Karl-Marx-Stadt.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] After graduating from high school in 1959, he fled as a refugee to West Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He studied political science and law at Marburg, where he also received his doctorate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In 1972, Gauland entered the Federal Press Office and worked as the Director of the Office of the Mayor of Frankfurt am Main for 10 years.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Afterwards, he became the head of a department of the Federal Ministry for the Environment, Nature Conservation, Building and Nuclear Safety in Bonn and Member of the Hessian Prime Minister's cabinet.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] From 1991 to 2006, he worked as an editor of the local newspaper *Märkische Allgemeine* in Potsdam.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] On the morning of 25 March 2010, German Chancellor Angela Merkel publicly promised there would be no direct financial aid to Greece, but reversed that statement hours later by agreeing with the leaders of the Euro countries to send the first of many "rescue packages" to Greece.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gerd Robanus, Assessor in the Federal Executive of the CDU-Business Association cited this as the reason for founding the Alternative for Germany together with Alexander Gauland, Konrad Adam and Bernd Lucke.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In February 2014, Gauland received about 80 percent of the vote during an Extraordinary National Congress in Diedersdorf, becoming chairman of the Brandenburg State Association of Alternative for Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] The AfD got 12.2 percent of the vote in the 2014 Brandenburg state election, enabling it to enter the assembly of that state for the first time.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] As part of this speech, after quoting Edmund Burke, Gauland wished the other members of parliament "all the strength and the courage, to tackle the tasks now ahead of them, in the interest of the voters and in the interest of the common good".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Before becoming an AfD founding member Gauland was a member of the CDU.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He is a supporter of a line that is both conservative on the societal level and liberal on the economic level.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He opposed the idea of an aid plan for Greece, which was then plunged into an economic crisis.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He called for the closure of Germany's and the European Union's borders, targeting Muslims in particular.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Alexander Gauland said he can not detect any right-wing extremists or radicals at the PEGIDA-Demonstrations.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland said: "I do not see right-wing extremists.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] I see citizens who demonstrate out of concern about developments in Germany, who are afraid.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In May 2016, Gauland reportedly made comments about Bayern Munich and black German international footballer Jérôme Boateng in a conversation with *Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung*.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] The paper cited Gauland, "people like [Boateng] as a footballer, but they don't want to have a Boateng as a neighbour".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] A controversy arose about this sentence.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland defended himself, saying he was fooled by the newspaper and it had been a background discussion, which was classified as confidential and thus not intended for publication.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland added that the effect of the statement – which in his words was meant descriptive – was distorted by the headline of the newspaper, "Gauland insults Boateng" (*Gauland beleidigt Boateng*).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] The newspaper had no audio recording of the statement, but independently written memos of two journalists.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] While Boateng himself stated that he was "saddened" by the statement of Gauland, the German federal government said it was "a vile and sad sentence" (*ein niederträchtiger und ein trauriger Satz*).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] But also the FAS was criticised for making "mistakes".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In September 2017, a video emerged of Gauland in which he said that Germany should "be proud of" its soldiers in both world wars and people should no longer "reproach" Germans for the Second World War.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He was quoted as saying: "If the French are rightly proud of their emperor and the Britons of Nelson and Churchill, we have the right to be proud of the achievements of the German soldiers in two world wars".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He continued, "If I look around Europe, no other people has dealt as clearly with their past wrongs as the Germans." In response, Germany's justice minister tweeted that the statements showed that Gauland's AfD was on the extreme right.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland's comment was defended by numerous right-leaning supporters both publicly and on social media.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In 2018, Gauland said "Hitler and the Nazis are just a speck of bird poop in more than 1,000 years of successful German history".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] From 2013 to 2017, he was party leader in the state Brandenburg and entered the Landtag of Brandenburg in the 2014 election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He resigned as party leader in Brandenburg, when he led the AfD in the 2017 German federal election next to Alice Weidel, with whom he's now leading the AfD group in the Bundestag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In December 2017, he was elected co-leader of the party next to Jörg Meuthen.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In November 2019, he resigned as party leader.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] In November 2024, Gauland announced that he would run for Bundestag again, this time in his birthtown of Chemnitz in the state of Saxony.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He was AfD's direct candidate in the eponymous district in the 2025 election, and was elected with 32.2% of the vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland's life companion Carola Hein is editor of a local newspaper, the *Märkische Allgemeine*, which he had previously edited.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] As a 26-year-old man, Gauland suffered from depression.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] He also suffered a heart attack in 2007, and has been taking medication to lower his blood pressure ever since.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] Gauland is a member of the Evangelical Church in Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-gauland] His daughter is a Protestant pastor and publicly distanced herself from her father's statements on refugees in 2016.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Previously, Lambsdorff served as a Member of the Bundestag (MP) from 2017 to 2023 and as Member of the European Parliament (MEP) from 2004 to 2017.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] A member of the former noble Lambsdorff family, his name reflects an Imperial Russian comital title.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Lambsdorff grew up in Hamburg, Brussels, and Bonn, attending the Catholic Academic High School Aloisiuskolleg at Bonn-Bad Godesberg until 1985, before going up to the University of Bonn.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] From 1991 until 1993, Lambsdorff studied at Georgetown University on a Fulbright Scholarship graduating as a MA in history and an MS in Foreign Service (1993).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] After diplomatic training, Lambsdorff served on the German Policy Planning Staff (together with Jorgo Chatzimarkakis, his contemporary and fellow FDP MEP) before becoming director of the Bundestag office of former German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, after the FDP left government in 1998.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Lambsdorff was first elected to the European Parliament in 2004 and was confirmed in 2009 and 2014.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Held in high regard, he was widely viewed as a possible successor to Graham Watson as leader of the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Group in the parliament, but the post went instead to Guy Verhofstadt.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] From 2011, Lambsdorff chaired the 12-member German FDP delegation in the European Parliament, before subsequently being elected Leader of the European Liberals and Democrats Group in 2014.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Until 2014, Lambsdorff served as member of the European Parliament's Committee on Foreign Affairs and the EU-Delegation for relations with the People's Republic of China.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] He also served as a deputy on the European Parliament Committee on Culture and Education and on the Delegation to the EU-Turkey Joint Parliamentary Committee DACP as well as the ACP–EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] During his tenure, he steered efforts to create a single EU-market for Defence and Security-related equipment as parliamentary rapporteur in 2009.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Following the 2014 elections to the European Parliament, Lambsdorff became a member of the European Parliament Committee on International Trade.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In this capacity, he has served as the parliament's rapporteur on the EU's agreement on the participation of Croatia in the European Economic Area.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Lambsdorff has led EU-Election Observer Missions on numerous occasions: as head of the EU-Election Observation Mission during the 2007–08 Kenyan crisis, he described the presidential elections as "flawed".
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Other elections he has overseen include the Bangladeshi general election in 2008, the first free Guinean presidential elections in 2010 and the Myanma general election in 2015.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In January 2014, at the FDP Convention in Bonn, Lambsdorff was elected as his party's lead candidate for the European Parliament elections receiving a resounding 86.2% of the vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] From 2014, Lambsdorff served as one of the fourteen Vice Presidents of the European Parliament who sit in for the president in presiding over the plenary.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In this capacity, he was also in charge of representing the parliament at multilateral bodies, including the United Nations and the World Trade Organization, as well as of the parliament's contacts with European business associations.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In addition, he was a member of the Democracy Support and Election Coordination Group (DEG), which oversees the Parliament's election observation missions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Lambsdorff has been a member of the German Bundestag since the 2017 national elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Throughout his time in parliament, he served as one of six deputy chairpersons of the FDP parliamentary group under the leadership of its successive chairs Christian Lindner (2017–2021) and Christian Dürr (since 2021), where he oversaw the group's activities on foreign policy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] From 2022, he also was a member of the Parliamentary Oversight Panel (PKGr), which provides parliamentary oversight of Germany's intelligence services BND, BfV and MAD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In addition, Lambsdorff chaired the German-Israeli Parliamentary Friendship Group.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Following the 2017 state elections in North Rhine-Westphalia, Lambsdorff was part of the FDP team in the negotiations with Armin Laschet's CDU on a coalition agreement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] He led his party's delegation in the working group on European affairs; his co-chair of the CDU was Matthias Kerkhoff.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In March 2024, Lambsdorff – alongside other EU ambassadors – attended the funeral of opposition leader Alexei Navalny.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Also in March 2024, Russia's foreign ministry summoned Lambsdorff again after Russian media published an audio recording of senior German military officials discussing weapons for Ukraine and a potential strike by Kyiv on a bridge in Crimea.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In February 2026, *Der Spiegel* reported that Lambsdorff would be dispatched to Tel Aviv in the coming summer, replacing Steffen Seibert.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] According to *Der Spiegel,* Lambsdorff would be succeeded in Moscow by the Ambassador to Mexico since 2024, Clemens von Goetze.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Lambsdorff has become increasingly critical of an accession of Turkey to the European Union and publicly declared that accession talks should be suspended until the Turkish government returns to the direction of the EU.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Along with his fellow parliamentarians Marietje Schaake, Ramon Tremosa and members of the Greens/EFA group, Lambsdorff nominated Leyla Yunus, imprisoned Azerbaijani human rights activist and director of the Institute of Peace and Democracy, for the 2014 Sakharov Prize.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] As a consequence of the European debt crisis, Lambsdorff told the *Financial Times Deutschland* in 2012 that it might make sense to give the European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs greater influence over euro-zone countries' budgets.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Following the 2014 European elections, Lambsdorff openly rejected Pierre Moscovici's nomination as European Commissioner for Economic and Financial Affairs, Taxation and Customs, stating that Moscovici should be held accountable for France's rising deficit and worsening economic situation.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In December 2014, Lambsdorff proposed that the English language should be mastered by servants of the public administration, and should later become an official language of Germany, in addition to German.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] According to Lambsdorff, as experienced in other countries with a good knowledge of English in public institutions, this should help to attract more skilled migrants to prevent labor shortage, to ease business for investors and to establish a more welcoming culture.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] As evaluated by a representative YouGov survey, 59 percent of all Germans would welcome the establishment of English as an official language in the whole European Union.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] Count Alexander Lambsdorff is a member of the Baltic branch of the noble Lambsdorff family; his family branch emigrated from Westphalia to the Baltic region in the early 15th century and was recognised as noble in Courland in 1620.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] The family owned large estates in modern-day Latvia and Estonia, and family members distinguished themselves as military officers in the service of the Russian Empire.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] One of Alexander Lambsdorff's ancestors, Count Matthias von der Wenge Lambsdorff, was a Russian general and was conferred the hereditary comital title in 1817 by Alexander I of Russia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In 1880 the family was authorised by royal licence to use the titles *Baron of the Wenge* and *Count of Lambsdorff* in the Kingdom of Prussia.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alexander-graf-lambsdorff] In 1994, Lambsdorff married Franziska von Klitzing, daughter of Werner von Klitzing (1934-2022) and his wife, Princess Osterlind of Wied, by whom he has two children.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Since November 2024, Franziska Brantner and Felix Banaszak have been co-leaders of the party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It currently holds 85 of the 630 seats in the Bundestag, having won 11% of first votes and 11.6% of second votes cast in the 2025 federal election, putting it in fourth place of the seven political parties by number of seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Its parliamentary co-leaders are Britta Haßelmann and Katharina Dröge.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens have been part of the federal government twice: first as a junior partner to the Social Democrats (SPD) from 1998 to 2005, and then with the SPD and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) in the traffic light coalition from the 2021 election until that coalition's collapse in 2024.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the Scholz cabinet, the Greens had five ministers, including Vice-Chancellor Robert Habeck and Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party holds seats in most of Germany's state legislatures, except Saarland, Thuringia and Brandenburg, and is a member of coalition governments in seven states.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Cem Özdemir, Minister-President of Baden-Württemberg, is the only Green head of government in Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Landtag of Baden-Württemberg is also the only state legislature in which Alliance 90/The Greens is the largest party; it is the second largest party in the legislatures of Berlin, Hamburg and Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens is a founding member of the European Green Party and the Greens–European Free Alliance group in the European Parliament.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It is currently the largest party in the G/EFA group, with 21 MEPs.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 2019 European election, Alliance 90/The Greens was the second largest party in Germany, winning 20.5% of votes cast.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party had 166,000 members in February 2025, making it the third largest party in Germany by membership.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Green Party was initially founded in West Germany as *Die Grünen* (the Greens) in January 1980.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It grew out of the anti-nuclear energy, environmental, peace, new left, and new social movements of the late 20th century.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Between 1977 and 1979 local parties running on on environmental and peace issues were established across West Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although most environmental and anti-nuclear activists were initially sceptical of these efforts, a lack of results from pressure group activity and early electoral successes meant the approach gained momentum and led to local groups amalgamating into state-level parties.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The West Berlin state branch of The Greens was founded as *Alternative Liste*, or precisely, *Alternative Liste für Demokratie und Umweltschutz* (AL; alternative list for democracy and environmental protection) in 1978 and became the official West Berlin branch of The Greens in 1980.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1993, it renamed to Alliance 90/The Greens Berlin after the merger with East Berlin's Greens and Alliance 90.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Hamburg state branch of the Green Party was called *Grün-Alternative Liste Hamburg* (GAL; green-alternative list) from its foundation in 1982 until 2012.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1984, it became the official Hamburg branch of The Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In July 1978 former Christian Democrat Herbert Gruhl founded *Grüne Aktion Zukunft* (GAZ - green action future) as the beginning of a process to establish a nationwide green party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In February 1979 an electoral alliance was established to contest the first democratic elections to the European Parliament later that year under the name *Sonstige Politische Vereinigung Die Grünen* (SPV-Die Grünen - alternative political alliance, the greens).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This included GAZ, GLU, *Grüne Liste Schleswig-Holstein* and the Action Group of Independent Germans (a pro-neutrality pacifist political party which had adopted pro-environment policies in the 1970s and was predominantly present in southern Germany).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Two members of the BBU's executive, Petra Kelly and Roland Vogt, also joined the alliance, and it was also supported by prominent writer Heinrich Böll and socialist activist Rudi Dutschke.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, not all local green groups supported the coalition, including the West Berlin *Alternative Liste* and the *Bunte Liste* (Multicoloured List) in Hamburg, the latter being a rival green party to the city's GLU branch.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Both of these lists were heavily influenced by the activism of the Communist League.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] SPV-Die Grünen ran on a platform advocating a nuclear-free Europe and a Europe of the Regions, and scored 3.2 percent of the vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] As German electoral law provided for a generous scheme for reimbursement of election expenses, providing them to all parties scoring at least 0.5 percent of the vote, the new formation netted 4.8 million deutschmarks, after spending just 300,000 on its campaign.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This money was spent on establishing state and national party infrastructure.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] SPV-Die Grünen's success led to increased activist interest, with membership rising to around 10,000 by the end of 1979, and the Alternative and Multicoloured Lists showing more interest in joining forces with the other green groups.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A congress in October 1979 to agree a programme for the national party led to heated disagreements over economic orientation and non-violence and whether dual membership with other parties was to be permitted.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the latter was resolved by agreeing to devolve decisions on membership to local branches, the former was overcome by the adoption of what would become known as the four pillars of green politics: ecology, social responsibility, grassroots democracy and non-violence.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Journalist and activist August Haußleiter claimed to have proposed these and secured the agreement of the leaders of the right (Gruhl) and left (Jürgen Reents) factions at the conference.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The nascent movement received a further boost the same month when the *Bremer Grüne Liste* became the first green party to win seats in a state parliament, securing four seats in Bremen's election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The political party **The Greens** (German: *Die Grünen*) sprung out of the wave of New Social Movements that were active in the 1970s, including environmentalist, anti-war, and anti-nuclear movements which can trace their origin to the student protests of 1968.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Officially founded as a German national party on 13 January 1980 in Karlsruhe, the party sought to give these movements political and parliamentary representation, as the pre-existing people's parties were not organised in a way to address their stated issues.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Its membership included organisers from former attempts to achieve institutional representation such as GLU and AUD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Opposition to pollution, use of nuclear power, NATO military action, and certain aspects of industrialised society were principal campaign issues.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party also championed sexual liberation and some of their members supported the abolition of age-of-consent laws.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The formation of a party was purportedly first discussed by movement leaders in 1978.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Important figures in the first years were – among others – Petra Kelly, Joschka Fischer, Gert Bastian, Lukas Beckmann, Rudolf Bahro, Joseph Beuys, Antje Vollmer, Herbert Gruhl, August Haußleiter, Luise Rinser, Dirk Schneider, Christian Ströbele, Jutta Ditfurth, Baldur Springmann and Werner Vogel.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1982, the conservative factions of the Greens broke away to form the Ecological Democratic Party (ÖDP).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They also tended to identify more closely with a culture of protest and civil disobedience, frequently clashing with police at demonstrations against nuclear weapons, nuclear energy, and the construction of a new runway (*Startbahn West*) at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Those who left the party at the time might have felt similarly about some of these issues, but did not identify with the forms of protest that Green party members took part in.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Among the important political issues at the time was the deployment of Pershing II IRBMs and nuclear-tipped cruise missiles by the U.S. and NATO on West German soil, generating strong opposition in the general population that found an outlet in mass demonstrations.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The newly formed party was able to draw on this popular movement to recruit support.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The state electoral success in Hesse and Hamburg saw the party holding the balance of power in both states.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Hamburg the party won nine seats in the June 1982 election and made an offer of terms for confidence and supply to the Social Democrats, but these were rejected.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the following December election the Greens lost a seat and the SPD won an absolute majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Hesse the Greens rejected the idea of cooperating with the SPD after the 1982 election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Another state election took place there the following year, resulting in the Greens losing two seats but no party achieving a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the election the state Greens voted to accept a confidence and supply agreement with the Social Democrats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Despite this negotiations immediately commenced over terms for a coalition agreement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although the party's Bundestag faction had limited success in legislating during the new MPs' first term, they were able to influence debate inside and outside parliament through proposing bills and asking questions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, the faction's efforts were disrupted by the attempt to implement rotation of members halfway through their terms as had been planned before the 1983 election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] All elected Bundestag members except Petra Kelly stepped down to enable rotation, however of the seven Green MEPs elected in the 1984 European election only three resigned from their roles.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The rotation stipulation was subsequently abolished, however the departure of many Bundestag members who had received significant media attention upon their entry to parliament led to reduced press interest in the parliamentary faction's work.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, elections in 1985 brought mixed results.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Contrastingly, in the West Berlin elections, after the SPD rejected the Alternative List's terms for a confidence and supply agreement before polling day, the SPD scored their worst post-war result of 32.4 percent, whilst the Greens almost doubled their vote to 10.6 percent and took 15 seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the SPD won 52.1 percent of the vote, the Greens failed to meet the electoral threshold with 4.6 percent.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Meanwhile, in local elections in Hesse both the SPD and Greens made gains, with the vote of the latter rising to 7.1 percent.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Shortly after Börner offered a coalition deal to the Greens which included the position of environment and energy minister.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Joschka Fischer took up the ministerial post, whilst Marita Haibach was made secretary of state for woman's affairs.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the federal party conference in Offenburg in December, the party's fundi faction, which had been hostile to the coalition agreement, took control of the party's executive.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1986, the intra-party conflict reduced somewhat.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A party conference in Hanover that Easter voted for an immediate end to nuclear power and the end of the coalition in Hesse.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] These attacks limited the party's gains to 0.6 percent of the vote, failing to add to the 11 seats won at the previous state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, in the Bavarian state election the party entered parliament for the first time, winning 7.5 percent of the vote and 15 seats, whilst in the Hamburg elections an all-female list secured 10.4 percent of votes and 13 seats, whilst neither the CDU or SPD secured a parliamentary majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Around this time, Joschka Fischer emerged as the unofficial leader of the party, which he remained until resigning all leadership posts following the 2005 federal election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the federal election, factional tensions over strategy re-emerged.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Hesse party withdrew from their coalition with the SPD, over the same nuclear enrichment plant which had led to the collapse of the previous confidence and supply agreement.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the subsequent 1987 Hessian state election, the SPD vote declined, leading to a coalition of Christian Democrats and Free Democrats entering government, but the Green vote increased to 9.4 percent, securing them 10 seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the Hamburg election held to resolve the deadlock resulting from the previous year's poll, the Green vote dropped to 7.1 percent, losing them five seats, whilst the SPD and FDP were able to form a coalition.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Meanwhile in Rhineland-Palatinate the Greens entered parliament for the first time, taking 5.9 percent of the vote and six seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Later that year in state elections in Schleswig-Holstein the state Green party, which was opposed to participating in any coalition, failed to enter parliament and won only 3.9 percent of the vote, whilst in Bremen they almost doubled their vote to 10.2 percent and won ten seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Tensions were further inflamed by the killing of two police officers and injury of nine others by autonomist activists at a protest at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the bulk of the party condemned the killings, some on the left including Ditfurth and Thomas Ebermann did not.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The growing disagreements at the federal level resulted in a crisis meeting in December 1987, following by a perspective congress in June 1988.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens were the target of attempts by the East German secret police to enlist the cooperation of members who were willing to align the party with the agenda of the German Democratic Republic.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party ranks included several politicians who were later discovered to have been Stasi agents, including Bundestag representative Dirk Schneider, European Parliament representative Brigitte Heinrich, and Red Army Faction defense lawyer Klaus Croissant.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Greens politician and Bundestag representative Gert Bastian was also a founding member of Generals for Peace, a pacifist group created and funded by the Stasi, the revelation of which may have contributed to the murder-suicide in which he killed his partner and Greens founder Petra Kelly.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A study commissioned by the Greens determined that 15 to 20 members intimately cooperated with the Stasi and another 450 to 500 had been informants.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Until 1987, the Greens included a faction involved in pedophile activism, the *SchwuP* short for *Arbeitsgemeinschaft "Schwule, Päderasten und Transsexuelle"* (approx.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] *working group "Gays, Pederasts and Transsexuals"*).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This faction campaigned for repealing § 176 of the German penal code, dealing with child sexual abuse.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This group was controversial within the party itself, and was seen as partly responsible for the poor election result of 1985.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This controversy re-surfaced in 2013 and chairwoman Claudia Roth stated she welcomed an independent scientific investigation on the extent of influence pedophile activists had on the party in the mid-1980s.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In November 2014, the political scientist Franz Walter presented the final report about his research on a press conference.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 1990 federal elections, taking place post-reunified Germany, the Greens in the West did not pass the 5% limit required to win seats in the Bundestag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It was only due to a temporary modification of German election law, applying the five-percent "hurdle" separately in East and West Germany, that the Greens acquired any parliamentary seats at all.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This happened because in the new states of Germany, the Greens, in a joint effort with Alliance 90, a heterogeneous grouping of civil rights activists, were able to gain more than 5% of the vote.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Some critics attribute this poor performance to the reluctance of the campaign to cater to the prevalent mood of nationalism, instead focusing on subjects such as global warming.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A campaign poster at the time proudly stated, "Everyone is talking about Germany; we're talking about the weather!", paraphrasing a popular slogan of Deutsche Bundesbahn, the German national railway.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party also opposed imminent reunification that was in process, instead wanting to initiate debates on ecology and nuclear issues before reunification causing a drop in support in Western Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the 1994 federal election; however, the merged party returned to the Bundestag, and the Greens received 7.3% of the vote nationwide and 49 seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 1998 federal election, despite a slight fall in their percentage of the vote (6.7%), the Greens retained 47 seats and joined the federal government for the first time in 'Red-Green' coalition government with the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Joschka Fischer became Vice-Chancellor of Germany and foreign minister in the new government, which had two other Green ministers (Andrea Fischer, later Renate Künast, and Jürgen Trittin).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Almost immediately the party was plunged into a crisis by the question of German participation in the NATO actions in Kosovo.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Numerous anti-war party members resigned their party membership when the first post-war deployment of German troops in a military conflict abroad occurred under a Red-Green government, and the party began to experience a long string of defeats in local and state-level elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 2001, the party experienced a further crisis as some Green Members of Parliament refused to back the government's plan of sending military personnel to help with the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Chancellor Gerhard Schröder called a vote of confidence, tying it to his strategy on the war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Four Green MPs and one Social Democrat voted against the government, but Schröder was still able to command a majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] On the other hand, the Greens achieved a major success as a governing party through the 2000 decision to phase out the use of nuclear energy.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Minister of Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety Jürgen Trittin reached an agreement with energy companies on the gradual phasing out of the country's nineteen nuclear power plants and a cessation of civil usage of nuclear power by 2020.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This was authorised through the Nuclear Exit Law.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Based on an estimate of 32 years as the normal period of operation for a nuclear power plant, the agreement defines precisely how much energy a power plant is allowed to produce before being shut down.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Despite the crises of the preceding electoral period, in the 2002 federal election, the Greens increased their total to 55 seats (in a smaller parliament) and 8.6%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens benefited from increased inroads among traditionally left-wing demographics which had benefited from Green-initiated legislation in the 1998–2002 term, such as environmentalists (Renewable Energies Act) and LGBT groups (Registered Partnership Law).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Perhaps most important for determining the success of both the Greens and the SPD was the increasing threat of war in Iraq, which was highly unpopular with the German public, and helped gather votes for the parties which had taken a stand against participation in this war.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] One internal issue in 2002 was the failed attempt to settle a long-standing discussion about the question of whether members of parliament should be allowed to become members of the party executive.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Two party conventions declined to change the party statute.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The necessary majority of two-thirds was missed by a small margin.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] As a result, former party chairpersons Fritz Kuhn and Claudia Roth (who had been elected to parliament that year) were no longer able to continue in their executive function and were replaced by former party secretary general Reinhard Bütikofer and former Bundestag member Angelika Beer.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party then held a member referendum on this question in the spring of 2003 which changed the party statute.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Now members of parliament may be elected for two of the six seats of the party executive, as long as they are not ministers or caucus leaders.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] 57% of all party members voted in the member referendum, with 67% voting in favor of the change.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The referendum was only the second in the history of Alliance 90/The Greens, the first having been held about the merger of the Greens and Alliance 90.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 2004, after Angelika Beer was elected to the European Parliament, Claudia Roth was elected to replace her as party chair.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The November 2003 party convention was held in Dresden and decided the election platform for the 2004 European Parliament elections.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The German Green list for these elections was headed by Rebecca Harms (then leader of the Green party in Lower Saxony) and Daniel Cohn-Bendit, previously Member of the European Parliament for The Greens of France.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The November 2003 convention is also noteworthy because it was the first convention of a German political party ever to use an electronic voting system.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens gained a record 13 of Germany's 99 seats in these elections, mainly due to the perceived competence of Green ministers in the federal government and the unpopularity of the Social Democratic Party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In early 2005, the Greens were the target of the German Visa Affair 2005, instigated in the media by the Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the end of April 2005, they celebrated the decommissioning of the Obrigheim nuclear power station.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They also continue to support a bill for an Anti-Discrimination Law (Allgemeines Gleichbehandlungsgesetz) in the Bundestag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In May 2005, the only remaining state-level red-green coalition government lost the vote in the North Rhine-Westphalia state election, leaving only the federal government with participation of the Greens (apart from local governments).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the early 2005 federal election the party incurred very small losses and achieved 8.1% of the vote and 51 seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, due to larger losses of the SPD, the previous coalition no longer had a majority in the Bundestag.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] For almost two years after the federal election in 2005, the Greens were not part of any government at the state or federal level.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In June 2007, the Greens in Bremen entered into a coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD) following the 2007 Bremen state election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In April 2008, following the 2008 Hamburg state election, the Green-Alternative List (GAL) in Hamburg entered into a coalition with the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), the first such state-level coalition in Germany.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although the GAL had to agree to the deepening of the Elbe River, the construction of a new coal-fired power station and two road projects they had opposed, they also received some significant concessions from the CDU.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] These included reforming state schools by increasing the number of primary school educational stages, the restoration of trams as public transportation in the city-state, and more pedestrian-friendly real estate development.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] On 29 November 2010, the coalition collapsed, resulting in an election that was won by SPD.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the Saarland state election of August 2009, The Greens held the balance of power after a close election where no two-party coalitions could create a stable majority government.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In June 2010, in the first state election following the victory of the CDU/CSU and FDP in the 2009 federal election, the "black-yellow" CDU-FDP coalition in North Rhine-Westphalia under Jürgen Rüttgers lost its majority.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] So a red-green government in a state where it was defeated under Peer Steinbrück in 2005 came into office again on 14 June 2010 with the election of Hannelore Kraft as minister-president (Cabinet Kraft I).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens founded the first international chapter of a German political party in the U.S. on 13 April 2008 at the Goethe-Institut in Washington D.C.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In March 2011 (two weeks after the Fukushima nuclear disaster had begun), the Greens made large gains in Rhineland-Palatinate and in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Baden-Württemberg they became the senior partner in a governing coalition for the first time.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Winfried Kretschmann is now the first Green to serve as Minister-President of a German State (Cabinet Kretschmann I and II).
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Polling data from August 2011 indicated that one in five Germans supported the Greens.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] From 4 October 2011 to 4 September 2016, the party was represented in all state parliaments.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Like the Social Democrats, the Greens backed Chancellor Angela Merkel on most bailout votes in the German parliament during her second term, saying their pro-European stances overrode party politics.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Shortly before the elections, the party plummeted to a four-year low in the polls, undermining efforts by Peer Steinbrück's Social Democrats to unseat Merkel.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] While being in opposition on the federal level since 2005, the Greens have established themselves as a powerful force in Germany's political system.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] By 2016, the Greens had joined 11 out of 16 state governments in a variety of coalitions.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Over the years, they have built up an informal structure called G-coordination to organize interests between the federal party office, the parliamentary group in the Bundestag, and the Greens governing on the state level.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens remained the smallest of six parties in the Bundestag in the 2017 federal election, winning 8.9% of votes.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the election, they entered into talks for a Jamaica coalition with the CDU and FDP.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Discussions collapsed after the FDP withdrew in November.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the federal election and unsuccessful Jamaica negotiations, the party held elections for two new co-leaders; incumbents Özdemir and Peter did not stand for re-election.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Robert Habeck and Annalena Baerbock were elected with 81% and 64% of votes, respectively.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Habeck had served as deputy premier and environment minister in Schleswig-Holstein since 2012, while Baerbock had been a leading figure in the party's Brandenburg branch since 2009.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Their election was considered a break with tradition, as they were both members of the moderate wing.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens saw a major surge in support during the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October 2018, becoming the second largest party in both.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They subsequently rose to second place behind the CDU/CSU in national polling, averaging between 17% and 20% over the next six months.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 2019 European Parliament election, the Greens achieved their best ever result in a national election, placing second with 20.5% of the vote and winning 21 seats.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] National polling released after the election showed a major boost for the party.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The first poll after the election, conducted by Forsa, showed the Greens in first place on 27%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This was the first time the Greens had ever been in first place in a national opinion poll, and the first time in the history of the Federal Republic that any party other than the CDU/CSU or SPD had placed first in a national poll.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This trend continued as polls from May to July showed the CDU/CSU and Greens trading first place, after which point the CDU/CSU pulled ahead once more.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens continued to poll in the low 20% range into early 2020.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens recorded best-ever results in the Brandenburg (10.8%) and Saxony (8.6%) state elections in September 2019, and subsequently joined coalition governments in both states.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They suffered an unexpected decline in the Thuringian election in October, only narrowing retaining their seats with 5.2%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the February 2020 Hamburg state election, the Greens became the second largest party, winning 24.2% of votes cast.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In March 2021, the Greens improved their performance in Baden-Württemberg, where they remained the strongest party with 32.6% of votes, and Rhineland-Palatinate, where they moved into third place with 9.3%.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Due to their sustained position as the second most popular party in national polling ahead of the September 2021 federal election, the Greens chose to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single Chancellor candidate.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Co-leader Annalena Baerbock was announced as Chancellor candidate on 19 April and formally confirmed on 12 June with 98.5% approval.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens surged in opinion polls in late April and May, briefly surpassing the CDU as the most popular party in the country, but their numbers slipped back after Baerbock was caught up in several controversies.
[src:2020-thuringian-government-crisis/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Her personal popularity also fell below that of both Armin Laschet and Olaf Scholz, the Chancellor candidates for the CDU and SPD, respectively.
